,'2018-12-11 19:24:15','2018-12-11 19:24:15','.parallax-mirror,.frontpage-banner, .juniper_750_500 ,#credit\n{\n	display:none;\n}\n\nbody\n{\n	margin-top:80px;\n	font-weight: 400;\n    font-size: 16px;\n}\n\n.navbar-default .navbar-nav>li>a {\n    color: #fff !important;\n}\n\n.navbar-default .navbar-brand, .navbar-default .navbar-brand:hover {\n    color: #fff !important;\n}\n\n#menu_row\n{\n	background:#1F984A !important;\n}\n\n.banner-wrap {\n    display: inline-block;\n    padding: 0px;\n}\n\n.form_allowed_tags{\n	display:none;\n}\n\n.frontpage-banner .banner-title, .subpage-banner .banner-title {\n    font-size: 55px;\n    color: #059855;\n    line-height: 100px;\n    text-transform: capitalize;\n    font-weight: 500;\n    padding-bottom: 25px;\n    /* text-shadow: 0px 0px 5px rgba(26, 26, 26, .5); */\n}\n\n.subpage-banner {\n       background: none !important;\n    padding: 0px !important;\n}\n.frontpage-banner .banner-title, .subpage-banner .banner-title {\n    font-size: 55px;\n    color: #059855;\n    line-height: 60px;\n    text-transform: capitalize;\n    font-weight: 500;\n    padding-bottom: 25px;\n    text-shadow: none;\n}\n.dropdown-menu\n{\n	    background: #1c8140;\n    border: 0px;\n}','juniper','','inherit','closed','closed','','27-revision-v1','','','2018-12-11 19:24:15','2018-12-11 19:24:15','',27,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/11/27-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(82,1,'2018-12-11 19:38:38','2018-12-11 19:38:38','','favicon-32x32','','inherit','open','closed','','favicon-32x32','','','2018-12-11 19:38:38','2018-12-11 19:38:38','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/favicon-32x32.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(83,1,'2018-12-11 19:38:48','2018-12-11 19:38:48','http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/cropped-favicon-32x32.png','cropped-favicon-32x32.png','','inherit','open','closed','','cropped-favicon-32x32-png','','','2018-12-11 19:38:48','2018-12-11 19:38:48','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/cropped-favicon-32x32.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(87,1,'2018-12-12 05:09:14','2018-12-12 05:09:14','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Merge multiple manifest files</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your APK file can contain just one&nbsp;<code>AndroidManifest.xml</code>&nbsp;file, but your Android Studio project may contain several—provided by the main source set, build variants, and imported libraries. So when building your app, the Gradle build merges all manifest files into a single manifest file that\'s packaged into your APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The manifest merger tool combines all XML elements from each file by following some merge heuristics and by obeying merge preferences that you have defined with special XML attributes. This page describes how manifest merging works and how you can apply merge preferences to resolve merge conflicts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Merge Priorities</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The merger tool combines all the manifest files into one file by merging them sequentially based on each manifest file\'s priority. For example, if you have three manifest files, the lowest priority manifest is merged into the next highest priority, and then that is merged into the highest priority manifest, as illustrated in figure</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/3oAxwUYi2vQOtECpKDHh4_OmIrJb43unkJvy1EO4fhQSxEbCUnJXF0_w7Pwoph4qfaYT_ijayQzTfPbOfhnocAKEve8rSrzxnMPxh1DZN7KA-0uYKKRzoCep-9wjJBNPd2KrpPH-AfI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>&nbsp;The process to merge three manifest files, lowest priority (left) into highest priority (right)<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"merge_rule_markers\">Merge rule markers</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A merge rule marker is an XML attribute you can use to express your preference about how to resolve merge conflicts or remove unwanted elements and attributes. You can apply a marker to either an entire element or to just specific attributes in an element.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When merging two manifest files, the merger tool looks for these markers in the higher-priority manifest file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All markers belong to the Android&nbsp;<code>tools</code>&nbsp;namespace, so you must first declare this namespace in the&nbsp;<code>&lt;manifest&gt;</code>&nbsp;element as shown here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;manifest xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; package=\"com.example.myapp\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>xmlns:tools=\"http://schemas.android.com/tools\"</strong>&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Node Markers</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To apply a merge rule to an entire XML element (to all attributes in a given manifest element and to all its child tags), use the following attributes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li> tools:node=\"merge\"</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Merge all attributes in this tag and all nested elements when there are no conflicts using the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. <strong>This is the default behavior for elements.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/eetGYsYRUdGcYjEoXidr2VZRITsNl3_x1xGYjUn0NDpeLOjZkgeFQLXA8jGONvBOfTKZcZL_i23esWOTnuDZT59XknVdqytL42oGHnjm-n7qC4Z8j4bix1TfUWVLBL3HdbvALT8N\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/snxh0rm5_oqA1OssNjvxUc3MABNsVa9OWAfrFJ-12AVQc07Xr_pKr9eW2KaAnyhls6qYknLLZ4LBhRZGePyqRnXX2j0U66-Xx2Wqagk5hwzWbVUG8oKqyj8xNJGgMonQWoybKSOV\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. </strong>tools:node=\"merge-only-attributes\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Merge attributes in this tag only; do not merge nested elements.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/SaxQbR1UKbX5PqOBTUMu7LrVhnsZkWLO1hVvh7hnXkHA7NvGhatbmiHAEbeWFfBHVaFvvrpxBFKWzuU1JsyL31kVoXrvrRdBmmAwXoXqmw05m6Y5OmfQ3FJcEaCYJuDjJlUKQk35\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"remove\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Remove this element from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you should instead just delete this element, using this is necessary when you discover an element in your merged manifest that you don\'t need, and it was provided by a lower-priority manifest file that\'s out of your control (such as an imported library).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/RTQeRod2z0wZakIowYSlwMij_EE8nFl6x8QDorm4D-fL6C1umWpnXmcYwOAFMJpOY7VTwqty195OfvJ7YWe6vr7xTTBmg_4NRiJTDJq8LJzMNeRtGMUxjzVyoYfhftRfVV4XO_NJ\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:remove=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remove the specified attributes from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you could instead just delete these attributes, it\'s necessary to use this when the lower-priority manifest file <em>does include</em> these attributes and you want to ensure they do not go into the merged manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/nT7MwFT-slYa6MNkWLt24dK91k6D1ubvyJfVjabC4LA9dsYJL3dTCQIo7gJd5I0mu29eqREnCKP2HOfy58f0tyE2W6EfU6TQ5SGaQV_6OwjOfVlBTlzZARPnDp6vlXXclk9KDELs\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. &nbsp;tools:node=\"removeAll\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Like tools:node=\"remove\", but it removes all elements matching this element type (within the same parent element).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/dYnRy7fWwNEuetvONcChdo3l_jpk4clmy2qWXFiuwpMkY3mAEdyG310sMCyO-qB-oWyeA0ag-49PDFft7B79setImuFxyyP0IpvZviTCBZ4lqdAaAxfzY0vdGmzFtnCWB1PnaS0a\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. &nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"replace\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Replace the lower-priority element completely. That is, if there is a matching element in the lower-priority manifest, ignore it and use this element exactly as it appears in this manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/53VWZWcV_8gJBGSnkLWwoqE6cG2cGtCutDggmKWrpMlnNLfrdDj9OVXhKEJ388pSQSlD15L6m1x2RTRC5ukUFhSnp8mqwZFBXEYwoHRvaf_UsiY66ZVPZZasTGk_jdidQdfkD_4_\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:replace=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace the specified attributes in the lower-priority manifest with those from this manifest. In other words, always keep the higher-priority manifest\'s values.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/TLJpaap_e8dekHHh1kLqMdz-50mSdTbv6mDEQwOc4k3tCkMbs67SGWj1mA-159XUiNmwZaTMdpHJCVbiQUuz4fFFrgqA2INGxQRz7UpRSwRx2byyOkAk-9y0ojvnY4Hgj4Hdxasp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. &nbsp;tools:node=\"strict\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Generate a build failure any time this element in the lower-priority manifest does not exactly match it in the higher-priority manifest (unless resolved by other merge rule markers). This overrides the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. For example, if the lower-priority manifest simply includes an extra attribute, the build fails (whereas the default behavior adds the extra attribtue to the merged manifest).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/UhdWJZiqDIs1QFemrjQQDCdHdRRDMCSfV8MmhduY_TMtRqX_9gm-LZaLCeC6W05pK9Ydhn6o8rfutkYmuk4X66u91Uk_iXLO6cORH2IbnrFuAqmjTXeHbl2Vy9Y2GmL1oAucbnbI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:strict=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Generate a build failure any time these attributes in the lower-priority manifest do not exactly match them in the higher-prority manifest. <strong>This is the default behavior for all attributes</strong>, except for those with special behaviors as described in the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/u4dINDK5ZOfecElJCJilPi11JebN8rPp9yayagG8v7qr2VPuSDElfbXQoNeWTo5VPubW64_ps2spN-_ryjzVYayq0u2a2TMZ4E3wwnJGIa7ecJxw4nGy3bSo2D9ntnLxDYe1SM8V\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note : You can also apply multiple markers to one element as follows.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/zfCROMLVwG293_CEftqngE1hKjp6_ysRlsVlTTnm4SxP87YKj5yiphner43wNsGcacA1XyPp7nfmHVv9sAsYrTpwm9BFdlx3YV-hIfQhCNff4ed-HbEa-u0nnsSyksstTlzjXphp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reference : </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers\">https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers</a></li><li></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Manifest Merge Rule','','publish','open','open','','manifest-merge-rule','','','2018-12-12 05:52:05','2018-12-12 05:52:05','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/?p=87',0,'post','',0),(88,1,'2018-12-12 05:09:14','2018-12-12 05:09:14','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Merge multiple manifest files</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your APK file can contain just one&nbsp;<code>AndroidManifest.xml</code>&nbsp;file, but your Android Studio project may contain several—provided by the main source set, build variants, and imported libraries. So when building your app, the Gradle build merges all manifest files into a single manifest file that\'s packaged into your APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The manifest merger tool combines all XML elements from each file by following some merge heuristics and by obeying merge preferences that you have defined with special XML attributes. This page describes how manifest merging works and how you can apply merge preferences to resolve merge conflicts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Merge Priorities</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The merger tool combines all the manifest files into one file by merging them sequentially based on each manifest file\'s priority. For example, if you have three manifest files, the lowest priority manifest is merged into the next highest priority, and then that is merged into the highest priority manifest, as illustrated in figure</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/3oAxwUYi2vQOtECpKDHh4_OmIrJb43unkJvy1EO4fhQSxEbCUnJXF0_w7Pwoph4qfaYT_ijayQzTfPbOfhnocAKEve8rSrzxnMPxh1DZN7KA-0uYKKRzoCep-9wjJBNPd2KrpPH-AfI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong> The process to merge three manifest files, lowest priority (left) into highest priority (right)<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"merge_rule_markers\">Merge rule markers</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A merge rule marker is an XML attribute you can use to express your preference about how to resolve merge conflicts or remove unwanted elements and attributes. You can apply a marker to either an entire element or to just specific attributes in an element.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When merging two manifest files, the merger tool looks for these markers in the higher-priority manifest file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All markers belong to the Android&nbsp;<code>tools</code>&nbsp;namespace, so you must first declare this namespace in the&nbsp;<code>&lt;manifest&gt;</code>&nbsp;element as shown here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;manifest xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; package=\"com.example.myapp\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>xmlns:tools=\"http://schemas.android.com/tools\"</strong>&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Node Markers</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To apply a merge rule to an entire XML element (to all attributes in a given manifest element and to all its child tags), use the following attributes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li> tools:node=\"merge\"</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Merge all attributes in this tag and all nested elements when there are no conflicts using the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. <strong>This is the default behavior for elements.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/eetGYsYRUdGcYjEoXidr2VZRITsNl3_x1xGYjUn0NDpeLOjZkgeFQLXA8jGONvBOfTKZcZL_i23esWOTnuDZT59XknVdqytL42oGHnjm-n7qC4Z8j4bix1TfUWVLBL3HdbvALT8N\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/snxh0rm5_oqA1OssNjvxUc3MABNsVa9OWAfrFJ-12AVQc07Xr_pKr9eW2KaAnyhls6qYknLLZ4LBhRZGePyqRnXX2j0U66-Xx2Wqagk5hwzWbVUG8oKqyj8xNJGgMonQWoybKSOV\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. </strong>tools:node=\"merge-only-attributes\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Merge attributes in this tag only; do not merge nested elements.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/SaxQbR1UKbX5PqOBTUMu7LrVhnsZkWLO1hVvh7hnXkHA7NvGhatbmiHAEbeWFfBHVaFvvrpxBFKWzuU1JsyL31kVoXrvrRdBmmAwXoXqmw05m6Y5OmfQ3FJcEaCYJuDjJlUKQk35\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"remove\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Remove this element from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you should instead just delete this element, using this is necessary when you discover an element in your merged manifest that you don\'t need, and it was provided by a lower-priority manifest file that\'s out of your control (such as an imported library).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/RTQeRod2z0wZakIowYSlwMij_EE8nFl6x8QDorm4D-fL6C1umWpnXmcYwOAFMJpOY7VTwqty195OfvJ7YWe6vr7xTTBmg_4NRiJTDJq8LJzMNeRtGMUxjzVyoYfhftRfVV4XO_NJ\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:remove=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remove the specified attributes from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you could instead just delete these attributes, it\'s necessary to use this when the lower-priority manifest file <em>does include</em> these attributes and you want to ensure they do not go into the merged manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/nT7MwFT-slYa6MNkWLt24dK91k6D1ubvyJfVjabC4LA9dsYJL3dTCQIo7gJd5I0mu29eqREnCKP2HOfy58f0tyE2W6EfU6TQ5SGaQV_6OwjOfVlBTlzZARPnDp6vlXXclk9KDELs\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. &nbsp;tools:node=\"removeAll\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Like tools:node=\"remove\", but it removes all elements matching this element type (within the same parent element).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/dYnRy7fWwNEuetvONcChdo3l_jpk4clmy2qWXFiuwpMkY3mAEdyG310sMCyO-qB-oWyeA0ag-49PDFft7B79setImuFxyyP0IpvZviTCBZ4lqdAaAxfzY0vdGmzFtnCWB1PnaS0a\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. &nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"replace\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Replace the lower-priority element completely. That is, if there is a matching element in the lower-priority manifest, ignore it and use this element exactly as it appears in this manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/53VWZWcV_8gJBGSnkLWwoqE6cG2cGtCutDggmKWrpMlnNLfrdDj9OVXhKEJ388pSQSlD15L6m1x2RTRC5ukUFhSnp8mqwZFBXEYwoHRvaf_UsiY66ZVPZZasTGk_jdidQdfkD_4_\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:replace=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace the specified attributes in the lower-priority manifest with those from this manifest. In other words, always keep the higher-priority manifest\'s values.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/TLJpaap_e8dekHHh1kLqMdz-50mSdTbv6mDEQwOc4k3tCkMbs67SGWj1mA-159XUiNmwZaTMdpHJCVbiQUuz4fFFrgqA2INGxQRz7UpRSwRx2byyOkAk-9y0ojvnY4Hgj4Hdxasp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. &nbsp;tools:node=\"strict\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Generate a build failure any time this element in the lower-priority manifest does not exactly match it in the higher-priority manifest (unless resolved by other merge rule markers). This overrides the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. For example, if the lower-priority manifest simply includes an extra attribute, the build fails (whereas the default behavior adds the extra attribtue to the merged manifest).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/UhdWJZiqDIs1QFemrjQQDCdHdRRDMCSfV8MmhduY_TMtRqX_9gm-LZaLCeC6W05pK9Ydhn6o8rfutkYmuk4X66u91Uk_iXLO6cORH2IbnrFuAqmjTXeHbl2Vy9Y2GmL1oAucbnbI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:strict=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Generate a build failure any time these attributes in the lower-priority manifest do not exactly match them in the higher-prority manifest. <strong>This is the default behavior for all attributes</strong>, except for those with special behaviors as described in the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/u4dINDK5ZOfecElJCJilPi11JebN8rPp9yayagG8v7qr2VPuSDElfbXQoNeWTo5VPubW64_ps2spN-_ryjzVYayq0u2a2TMZ4E3wwnJGIa7ecJxw4nGy3bSo2D9ntnLxDYe1SM8V\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note : You can also apply multiple markers to one element as follows.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/zfCROMLVwG293_CEftqngE1hKjp6_ysRlsVlTTnm4SxP87YKj5yiphner43wNsGcacA1XyPp7nfmHVv9sAsYrTpwm9BFdlx3YV-hIfQhCNff4ed-HbEa-u0nnsSyksstTlzjXphp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:nextpage -->\n<!--nextpage-->\n<!-- /wp:nextpage -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reference : </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<p>https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers</p>\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\nhttps://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Manifest Merge Rule','','inherit','closed','closed','','87-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:09:14','2018-12-12 05:09:14','',87,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/87-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(90,1,'2018-12-12 05:12:13','2018-12-12 05:12:13','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Merge multiple manifest files</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your APK file can contain just one&nbsp;<code>AndroidManifest.xml</code>&nbsp;file, but your Android Studio project may contain several—provided by the main source set, build variants, and imported libraries. So when building your app, the Gradle build merges all manifest files into a single manifest file that\'s packaged into your APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The manifest merger tool combines all XML elements from each file by following some merge heuristics and by obeying merge preferences that you have defined with special XML attributes. This page describes how manifest merging works and how you can apply merge preferences to resolve merge conflicts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Merge Priorities</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The merger tool combines all the manifest files into one file by merging them sequentially based on each manifest file\'s priority. For example, if you have three manifest files, the lowest priority manifest is merged into the next highest priority, and then that is merged into the highest priority manifest, as illustrated in figure</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/3oAxwUYi2vQOtECpKDHh4_OmIrJb43unkJvy1EO4fhQSxEbCUnJXF0_w7Pwoph4qfaYT_ijayQzTfPbOfhnocAKEve8rSrzxnMPxh1DZN7KA-0uYKKRzoCep-9wjJBNPd2KrpPH-AfI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong> The process to merge three manifest files, lowest priority (left) into highest priority (right)<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"merge_rule_markers\">Merge rule markers</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A merge rule marker is an XML attribute you can use to express your preference about how to resolve merge conflicts or remove unwanted elements and attributes. You can apply a marker to either an entire element or to just specific attributes in an element.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When merging two manifest files, the merger tool looks for these markers in the higher-priority manifest file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All markers belong to the Android&nbsp;<code>tools</code>&nbsp;namespace, so you must first declare this namespace in the&nbsp;<code>&lt;manifest&gt;</code>&nbsp;element as shown here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;manifest xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; package=\"com.example.myapp\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>xmlns:tools=\"http://schemas.android.com/tools\"</strong>&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Node Markers</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To apply a merge rule to an entire XML element (to all attributes in a given manifest element and to all its child tags), use the following attributes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li> tools:node=\"merge\"</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Merge all attributes in this tag and all nested elements when there are no conflicts using the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. <strong>This is the default behavior for elements.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/eetGYsYRUdGcYjEoXidr2VZRITsNl3_x1xGYjUn0NDpeLOjZkgeFQLXA8jGONvBOfTKZcZL_i23esWOTnuDZT59XknVdqytL42oGHnjm-n7qC4Z8j4bix1TfUWVLBL3HdbvALT8N\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/snxh0rm5_oqA1OssNjvxUc3MABNsVa9OWAfrFJ-12AVQc07Xr_pKr9eW2KaAnyhls6qYknLLZ4LBhRZGePyqRnXX2j0U66-Xx2Wqagk5hwzWbVUG8oKqyj8xNJGgMonQWoybKSOV\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. </strong>tools:node=\"merge-only-attributes\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Merge attributes in this tag only; do not merge nested elements.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/SaxQbR1UKbX5PqOBTUMu7LrVhnsZkWLO1hVvh7hnXkHA7NvGhatbmiHAEbeWFfBHVaFvvrpxBFKWzuU1JsyL31kVoXrvrRdBmmAwXoXqmw05m6Y5OmfQ3FJcEaCYJuDjJlUKQk35\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"remove\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Remove this element from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you should instead just delete this element, using this is necessary when you discover an element in your merged manifest that you don\'t need, and it was provided by a lower-priority manifest file that\'s out of your control (such as an imported library).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/RTQeRod2z0wZakIowYSlwMij_EE8nFl6x8QDorm4D-fL6C1umWpnXmcYwOAFMJpOY7VTwqty195OfvJ7YWe6vr7xTTBmg_4NRiJTDJq8LJzMNeRtGMUxjzVyoYfhftRfVV4XO_NJ\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:remove=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remove the specified attributes from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you could instead just delete these attributes, it\'s necessary to use this when the lower-priority manifest file <em>does include</em> these attributes and you want to ensure they do not go into the merged manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/nT7MwFT-slYa6MNkWLt24dK91k6D1ubvyJfVjabC4LA9dsYJL3dTCQIo7gJd5I0mu29eqREnCKP2HOfy58f0tyE2W6EfU6TQ5SGaQV_6OwjOfVlBTlzZARPnDp6vlXXclk9KDELs\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. &nbsp;tools:node=\"removeAll\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Like tools:node=\"remove\", but it removes all elements matching this element type (within the same parent element).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/dYnRy7fWwNEuetvONcChdo3l_jpk4clmy2qWXFiuwpMkY3mAEdyG310sMCyO-qB-oWyeA0ag-49PDFft7B79setImuFxyyP0IpvZviTCBZ4lqdAaAxfzY0vdGmzFtnCWB1PnaS0a\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. &nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"replace\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Replace the lower-priority element completely. That is, if there is a matching element in the lower-priority manifest, ignore it and use this element exactly as it appears in this manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/53VWZWcV_8gJBGSnkLWwoqE6cG2cGtCutDggmKWrpMlnNLfrdDj9OVXhKEJ388pSQSlD15L6m1x2RTRC5ukUFhSnp8mqwZFBXEYwoHRvaf_UsiY66ZVPZZasTGk_jdidQdfkD_4_\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:replace=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace the specified attributes in the lower-priority manifest with those from this manifest. In other words, always keep the higher-priority manifest\'s values.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/TLJpaap_e8dekHHh1kLqMdz-50mSdTbv6mDEQwOc4k3tCkMbs67SGWj1mA-159XUiNmwZaTMdpHJCVbiQUuz4fFFrgqA2INGxQRz7UpRSwRx2byyOkAk-9y0ojvnY4Hgj4Hdxasp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. &nbsp;tools:node=\"strict\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Generate a build failure any time this element in the lower-priority manifest does not exactly match it in the higher-priority manifest (unless resolved by other merge rule markers). This overrides the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. For example, if the lower-priority manifest simply includes an extra attribute, the build fails (whereas the default behavior adds the extra attribtue to the merged manifest).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/UhdWJZiqDIs1QFemrjQQDCdHdRRDMCSfV8MmhduY_TMtRqX_9gm-LZaLCeC6W05pK9Ydhn6o8rfutkYmuk4X66u91Uk_iXLO6cORH2IbnrFuAqmjTXeHbl2Vy9Y2GmL1oAucbnbI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:strict=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Generate a build failure any time these attributes in the lower-priority manifest do not exactly match them in the higher-prority manifest. <strong>This is the default behavior for all attributes</strong>, except for those with special behaviors as described in the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/u4dINDK5ZOfecElJCJilPi11JebN8rPp9yayagG8v7qr2VPuSDElfbXQoNeWTo5VPubW64_ps2spN-_ryjzVYayq0u2a2TMZ4E3wwnJGIa7ecJxw4nGy3bSo2D9ntnLxDYe1SM8V\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note : You can also apply multiple markers to one element as follows.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/zfCROMLVwG293_CEftqngE1hKjp6_ysRlsVlTTnm4SxP87YKj5yiphner43wNsGcacA1XyPp7nfmHVv9sAsYrTpwm9BFdlx3YV-hIfQhCNff4ed-HbEa-u0nnsSyksstTlzjXphp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reference : </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers\" target=\"_blank\">https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers</a>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Manifest Merge Rule','','inherit','closed','closed','','87-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:12:13','2018-12-12 05:12:13','',87,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/87-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(92,1,'2018-12-12 05:40:23','2018-12-12 05:40:23','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Entity</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">User</span> </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@PrimaryKey</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> uid;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"first_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String firstName;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"last_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String lastName;\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">UserDao</span> </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\">List&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">getAll</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\">List&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadAllByIds</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span>[] userIds)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\">User <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">findByName</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String first, String last)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertAll</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Delete</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">delete</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User user)</span></span>;\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Database</span>(entities = {User.class}, version = <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">1</span>)\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">AppDatabase</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">RoomDatabase</span> </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> UserDao <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">userDao</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),\n        AppDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"database-name\"</span>).build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertBothUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User user1, User user2)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertUsersAndFriends</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User user, List&lt;User&gt; friends)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Update</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">updateUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Delete</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">deleteUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> User[] loadAllUsers();\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> minAge);\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> minAge, <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> maxAge);\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"OR last_name LIKE :search\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">findUserWithName</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String search)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">NameTuple</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"first_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String firstName;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"last_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String lastName;\n\n}\n\n<span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;NameTuple&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadFullName</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;NameTuple&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadUsersFromRegions</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(List&lt;String&gt; regions)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">app/build.gradle</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">dependencies {\n\n    implementation <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</span>\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Flowable&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadUserById</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> id)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Emits the number of users added to the database.</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertLargeNumberOfUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(List&lt;User&gt; users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Completable <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertLargeNumberOfUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at\n       least one user. */</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Delete</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Single&lt;Integer&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">deleteUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(List&lt;User&gt; users)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Cursor <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadRawUsersOlderThan</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> minAge)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM book \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\"</span>)\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;Book&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">findBooksBorrowedByNameSync</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String userName)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \"</span> +\n          <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"FROM user, pet \"</span> +\n          <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\"</span>)\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</span>\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// \"public\" access modifier.</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">UserPet</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String userName;\n       <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String petName;\n   }\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Best way to Run Room queries in background threads</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Never use&nbsp;<em>allowMainThreadQueries()&nbsp;</em></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You might be referring&nbsp;to many blogs and medium posts for implementing Room other than official Android documentation. One thing I found in them was the use of&nbsp;<em>allowMainThreadQueries()</em>&nbsp;method! You should never ever use this method for building your database class. You have to use another thread for all database queries (Especially for queries with insert/update/delete).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Never use AsyncTask.class for your queries</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When I have proposed the ban on allowMainThreadQueries(), You may be thinking of implementing an AsycTask class for your database queries. Sometimes AsyncTask also fails to make your DB queries. Once you go through the AsyncTask documentation you can find something like <a href=\"https://www.techeos.com/posts/android-workmanager-api-finally/\">this</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>AsyncTasks should ideally be used for short operations (a few seconds at the most.) If you need to keep threads running for long periods of time, it is highly recommended you use the various APIs provided by&nbsp;</em>the package<em><code>java.util.concurrent</code></em><em>&nbsp;such&nbsp;</em>as,<em><code><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/java/util/concurrent/Executor.html\">Executor</a></code></em><em><code><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/java/util/concurrent/ThreadPoolExecutor.html\">ThreadPoolExecutor</a></code>&nbsp;</em>and.<em><code><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/java/util/concurrent/FutureTask.html\">FutureTask</a></code></em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So you must move your queries to any services or any other thread maintainers. A simple example using Executor.class is given below.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">Executor myExecutor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();\nmyExecutor.execute<span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(() -&gt; {\n    myDao.insert(userObject);\n})</span>;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Use&nbsp;<em>synchronized</em>&nbsp;for accessing database</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Usually, you only need one instance of the Room database for the whole app. In order to maintain this implementation, You have to create a singleton instance which gives the database instance using the synchronized method. So that, You can ensure the concurrent access of database is synchronized along the whole thread.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">//Sample database<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\"> instance </span>class.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">\nstatic</span> UserDatabase INSTANCE;\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">\npublic</span><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\"> static</span> UserDatabase getDatabase(final Context context) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\"> if </span>(INSTANCE == null) {\n        synchronized (UserDatabase.class) {\n           <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\"> if </span>(INSTANCE == null) {\n                INSTANCE = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),\n                        UserDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"database_name\"</span>)\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">                        .build</span>();\n\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\"> return </span>INSTANCE;\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Bundle your queries together in DAO interface</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your query abstract function uses another&nbsp;two queries function, You can wrap them together in your DAO class. So that you can avoid boilerplate codes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">UserDao</span> </span>{\n    \n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//Bundles to calls together here.</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Transaction</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">open</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">fun</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">updateData</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(users: <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">User</span>&gt;)</span></span> {\n        deleteAllUsers()\n        insertAll(users)\n    }\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">fun</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertAll</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(users: <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">User</span>&gt;)</span></span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query(<span class=\"hljs-meta-string\">\"DELETE FROM Users\"</span>)</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">fun</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">deleteAllUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a>&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','publish','open','open','','android-room-database','','\nhttps://www.techeos.com/posts/android-workmanager-api-finally/','2019-10-18 09:06:32','2019-10-18 08:06:32','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/?p=92',0,'post','',41),(93,1,'2018-12-12 05:40:23','2018-12-12 05:40:23','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong> Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a> should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a> by calling <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a> or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong> Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong> Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Entity<br>public class User {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @PrimaryKey<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public int uid;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String firstName;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String lastName;<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; getAll();<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Insert<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Delete<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 1)<br>public abstract class AppDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public abstract UserDao userDao();<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AppDatabase.class, \"database-name\").build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include <code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code> in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of <code>AppDatabase</code> in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of <code>AppDatabase</code> within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertBothUsers(User user1, User user2);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsersAndFriends(User user, List&lt;User&gt; friends);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Update</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void updateUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void deleteUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsers();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>@Dao</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(int minAge, int maxAge);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"OR last_name LIKE :search\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;User&gt; findUserWithName(String search);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public class NameTuple {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String firstName;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String lastName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadFullName();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadUsersFromRegions(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>app/build.gradle</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>dependencies {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;implementation \'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Flowable&lt;User&gt; loadUserById(int id);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Emits the number of users added to the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; insertLargeNumberOfUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Completable insertLargeNumberOfUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;least one user. */</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Single&lt;Integer&gt; deleteUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Cursor loadRawUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM book \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;Book&gt; findBooksBorrowedByNameSync(String userName);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"FROM user, pet \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// \"public\" access modifier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;static class UserPet {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String userName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String petName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:nextpage -->\n<!--nextpage-->\n<!-- /wp:nextpage -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Room Library Migration</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\" target=\"_blank\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n <a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\" target=\"_blank\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:core-embed/wordpress {\"url\":\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\",\"type\":\"wp-embed\",\"providerNameSlug\":\"simplified-coding\",\"className\":\"\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-embed-wordpress wp-block-embed is-type-wp-embed is-provider-simplified-coding\"><div class=\"wp-block-embed__wrapper\">\nhttps://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\n</div></figure>\n<!-- /wp:core-embed/wordpress -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:40:23','2018-12-12 05:40:23','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(111,1,'2018-12-12 05:48:25','2018-12-12 05:48:25','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Entity<br>public class User {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @PrimaryKey<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public int uid;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String firstName;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String lastName;<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; getAll();<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Insert<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Delete<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 1)<br>public abstract class AppDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public abstract UserDao userDao();<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AppDatabase.class, \"database-name\").build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertBothUsers(User user1, User user2);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsersAndFriends(User user, List&lt;User&gt; friends);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Update</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void updateUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void deleteUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsers();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>@Dao</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(int minAge, int maxAge);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"OR last_name LIKE :search\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;User&gt; findUserWithName(String search);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public class NameTuple {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String firstName;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String lastName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadFullName();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadUsersFromRegions(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>app/build.gradle</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>dependencies {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;implementation \'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Flowable&lt;User&gt; loadUserById(int id);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Emits the number of users added to the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; insertLargeNumberOfUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Completable insertLargeNumberOfUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;least one user. */</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Single&lt;Integer&gt; deleteUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Cursor loadRawUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM book \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;Book&gt; findBooksBorrowedByNameSync(String userName);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"FROM user, pet \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// \"public\" access modifier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;static class UserPet {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String userName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String petName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:nextpage -->\n<!--nextpage-->\n<!-- /wp:nextpage -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Room Library Migration</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:48:25','2018-12-12 05:48:25','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(112,1,'2018-12-12 05:48:42','2018-12-12 05:48:42','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Entity<br>public class User {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @PrimaryKey<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public int uid;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String firstName;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String lastName;<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; getAll();<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Insert<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Delete<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 1)<br>public abstract class AppDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public abstract UserDao userDao();<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AppDatabase.class, \"database-name\").build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertBothUsers(User user1, User user2);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsersAndFriends(User user, List&lt;User&gt; friends);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Update</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void updateUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void deleteUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsers();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>@Dao</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(int minAge, int maxAge);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"OR last_name LIKE :search\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;User&gt; findUserWithName(String search);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public class NameTuple {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String firstName;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String lastName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadFullName();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadUsersFromRegions(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>app/build.gradle</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>dependencies {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;implementation \'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Flowable&lt;User&gt; loadUserById(int id);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Emits the number of users added to the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; insertLargeNumberOfUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Completable insertLargeNumberOfUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;least one user. */</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Single&lt;Integer&gt; deleteUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Cursor loadRawUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM book \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;Book&gt; findBooksBorrowedByNameSync(String userName);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"FROM user, pet \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// \"public\" access modifier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;static class UserPet {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String userName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String petName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:nextpage -->\n<!--nextpage-->\n<!-- /wp:nextpage -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Room Library Migration</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:48:42','2018-12-12 05:48:42','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(116,1,'2018-12-12 05:50:59','2018-12-12 05:50:59','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Merge multiple manifest files</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Your APK file can contain just one&nbsp;<code>AndroidManifest.xml</code>&nbsp;file, but your Android Studio project may contain several—provided by the main source set, build variants, and imported libraries. So when building your app, the Gradle build merges all manifest files into a single manifest file that\'s packaged into your APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The manifest merger tool combines all XML elements from each file by following some merge heuristics and by obeying merge preferences that you have defined with special XML attributes. This page describes how manifest merging works and how you can apply merge preferences to resolve merge conflicts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Merge Priorities</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The merger tool combines all the manifest files into one file by merging them sequentially based on each manifest file\'s priority. For example, if you have three manifest files, the lowest priority manifest is merged into the next highest priority, and then that is merged into the highest priority manifest, as illustrated in figure</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/3oAxwUYi2vQOtECpKDHh4_OmIrJb43unkJvy1EO4fhQSxEbCUnJXF0_w7Pwoph4qfaYT_ijayQzTfPbOfhnocAKEve8rSrzxnMPxh1DZN7KA-0uYKKRzoCep-9wjJBNPd2KrpPH-AfI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>&nbsp;The process to merge three manifest files, lowest priority (left) into highest priority (right)<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"merge_rule_markers\">Merge rule markers</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A merge rule marker is an XML attribute you can use to express your preference about how to resolve merge conflicts or remove unwanted elements and attributes. You can apply a marker to either an entire element or to just specific attributes in an element.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When merging two manifest files, the merger tool looks for these markers in the higher-priority manifest file.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All markers belong to the Android&nbsp;<code>tools</code>&nbsp;namespace, so you must first declare this namespace in the&nbsp;<code>&lt;manifest&gt;</code>&nbsp;element as shown here:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;manifest xmlns:android=\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; package=\"com.example.myapp\"<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; <strong>xmlns:tools=\"http://schemas.android.com/tools\"</strong>&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Node Markers</strong><br></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To apply a merge rule to an entire XML element (to all attributes in a given manifest element and to all its child tags), use the following attributes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li> tools:node=\"merge\"</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Merge all attributes in this tag and all nested elements when there are no conflicts using the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. <strong>This is the default behavior for elements.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/eetGYsYRUdGcYjEoXidr2VZRITsNl3_x1xGYjUn0NDpeLOjZkgeFQLXA8jGONvBOfTKZcZL_i23esWOTnuDZT59XknVdqytL42oGHnjm-n7qC4Z8j4bix1TfUWVLBL3HdbvALT8N\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/snxh0rm5_oqA1OssNjvxUc3MABNsVa9OWAfrFJ-12AVQc07Xr_pKr9eW2KaAnyhls6qYknLLZ4LBhRZGePyqRnXX2j0U66-Xx2Wqagk5hwzWbVUG8oKqyj8xNJGgMonQWoybKSOV\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2. </strong>tools:node=\"merge-only-attributes\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Merge attributes in this tag only; do not merge nested elements.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/SaxQbR1UKbX5PqOBTUMu7LrVhnsZkWLO1hVvh7hnXkHA7NvGhatbmiHAEbeWFfBHVaFvvrpxBFKWzuU1JsyL31kVoXrvrRdBmmAwXoXqmw05m6Y5OmfQ3FJcEaCYJuDjJlUKQk35\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"remove\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Remove this element from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you should instead just delete this element, using this is necessary when you discover an element in your merged manifest that you don\'t need, and it was provided by a lower-priority manifest file that\'s out of your control (such as an imported library).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/RTQeRod2z0wZakIowYSlwMij_EE8nFl6x8QDorm4D-fL6C1umWpnXmcYwOAFMJpOY7VTwqty195OfvJ7YWe6vr7xTTBmg_4NRiJTDJq8LJzMNeRtGMUxjzVyoYfhftRfVV4XO_NJ\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:remove=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Remove the specified attributes from the merged manifest. Although it seems like you could instead just delete these attributes, it\'s necessary to use this when the lower-priority manifest file <em>does include</em> these attributes and you want to ensure they do not go into the merged manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/nT7MwFT-slYa6MNkWLt24dK91k6D1ubvyJfVjabC4LA9dsYJL3dTCQIo7gJd5I0mu29eqREnCKP2HOfy58f0tyE2W6EfU6TQ5SGaQV_6OwjOfVlBTlzZARPnDp6vlXXclk9KDELs\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4. &nbsp;tools:node=\"removeAll\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Like tools:node=\"remove\", but it removes all elements matching this element type (within the same parent element).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/dYnRy7fWwNEuetvONcChdo3l_jpk4clmy2qWXFiuwpMkY3mAEdyG310sMCyO-qB-oWyeA0ag-49PDFft7B79setImuFxyyP0IpvZviTCBZ4lqdAaAxfzY0vdGmzFtnCWB1PnaS0a\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>5. &nbsp;&nbsp;tools:node=\"replace\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Replace the lower-priority element completely. That is, if there is a matching element in the lower-priority manifest, ignore it and use this element exactly as it appears in this manifest.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/53VWZWcV_8gJBGSnkLWwoqE6cG2cGtCutDggmKWrpMlnNLfrdDj9OVXhKEJ388pSQSlD15L6m1x2RTRC5ukUFhSnp8mqwZFBXEYwoHRvaf_UsiY66ZVPZZasTGk_jdidQdfkD_4_\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:replace=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Replace the specified attributes in the lower-priority manifest with those from this manifest. In other words, always keep the higher-priority manifest\'s values.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/TLJpaap_e8dekHHh1kLqMdz-50mSdTbv6mDEQwOc4k3tCkMbs67SGWj1mA-159XUiNmwZaTMdpHJCVbiQUuz4fFFrgqA2INGxQRz7UpRSwRx2byyOkAk-9y0ojvnY4Hgj4Hdxasp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>6. &nbsp;tools:node=\"strict\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>	Generate a build failure any time this element in the lower-priority manifest does not exactly match it in the higher-priority manifest (unless resolved by other merge rule markers). This overrides the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>. For example, if the lower-priority manifest simply includes an extra attribute, the build fails (whereas the default behavior adds the extra attribtue to the merged manifest).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/UhdWJZiqDIs1QFemrjQQDCdHdRRDMCSfV8MmhduY_TMtRqX_9gm-LZaLCeC6W05pK9Ydhn6o8rfutkYmuk4X66u91Uk_iXLO6cORH2IbnrFuAqmjTXeHbl2Vy9Y2GmL1oAucbnbI\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>tools:strict=\"<strong>attr, ...</strong>\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Generate a build failure any time these attributes in the lower-priority manifest do not exactly match them in the higher-prority manifest. <strong>This is the default behavior for all attributes</strong>, except for those with special behaviors as described in the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_conflict_heuristics\">merge conflict heuristics</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/u4dINDK5ZOfecElJCJilPi11JebN8rPp9yayagG8v7qr2VPuSDElfbXQoNeWTo5VPubW64_ps2spN-_ryjzVYayq0u2a2TMZ4E3wwnJGIa7ecJxw4nGy3bSo2D9ntnLxDYe1SM8V\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Note : You can also apply multiple markers to one element as follows.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/zfCROMLVwG293_CEftqngE1hKjp6_ysRlsVlTTnm4SxP87YKj5yiphner43wNsGcacA1XyPp7nfmHVv9sAsYrTpwm9BFdlx3YV-hIfQhCNff4ed-HbEa-u0nnsSyksstTlzjXphp\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reference : </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers\">https://developer.android.com/studio/build/manifest-merge#merge_rule_markers</a></li><li></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Manifest Merge Rule','','inherit','closed','closed','','87-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:50:59','2018-12-12 05:50:59','',87,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/87-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(118,1,'2018-12-12 05:53:03','2018-12-12 05:53:03','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Entity<br>public class User {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @PrimaryKey<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public int uid;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String firstName;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String lastName;<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; getAll();<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Insert<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Delete<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 1)<br>public abstract class AppDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public abstract UserDao userDao();<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AppDatabase.class, \"database-name\").build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertBothUsers(User user1, User user2);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsersAndFriends(User user, List&lt;User&gt; friends);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Update</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void updateUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void deleteUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsers();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>@Dao</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(int minAge, int maxAge);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"OR last_name LIKE :search\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;User&gt; findUserWithName(String search);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public class NameTuple {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String firstName;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String lastName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadFullName();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadUsersFromRegions(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>app/build.gradle</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>dependencies {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;implementation \'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Flowable&lt;User&gt; loadUserById(int id);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Emits the number of users added to the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; insertLargeNumberOfUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Completable insertLargeNumberOfUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;least one user. */</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Single&lt;Integer&gt; deleteUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Cursor loadRawUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM book \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;Book&gt; findBooksBorrowedByNameSync(String userName);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"FROM user, pet \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// \"public\" access modifier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;static class UserPet {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String userName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String petName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:53:03','2018-12-12 05:53:03','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(122,1,'2018-12-12 05:56:00','2018-12-12 05:56:00','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Entity<br>public class User {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @PrimaryKey<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public int uid;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String firstName;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String lastName;<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; getAll();<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Insert<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Delete<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 1)<br>public abstract class AppDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public abstract UserDao userDao();<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AppDatabase.class, \"database-name\").build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertBothUsers(User user1, User user2);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void insertUsersAndFriends(User user, List&lt;User&gt; friends);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Update</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void updateUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public void deleteUsers(User... users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsers();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>@Dao</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(int minAge, int maxAge);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"OR last_name LIKE :search\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;User&gt; findUserWithName(String search);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public class NameTuple {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String firstName;<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String lastName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadFullName();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;NameTuple&gt; loadUsersFromRegions(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>app/build.gradle</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>dependencies {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;implementation \'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Flowable&lt;User&gt; loadUserById(int id);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Emits the number of users added to the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; insertLargeNumberOfUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Completable insertLargeNumberOfUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;least one user. */</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Single&lt;Integer&gt; deleteUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Cursor loadRawUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM book \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;Book&gt; findBooksBorrowedByNameSync(String userName);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"FROM user, pet \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// \"public\" access modifier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;static class UserPet {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String userName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String petName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a> </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 05:56:00','2018-12-12 05:56:00','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(131,1,'2018-12-12 06:11:33','2018-12-12 06:11:33','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()\n,UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n               		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()\n               		.build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Database</span>(entities = {User.class},version = <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>)\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">UsersDatabase</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">RoomDatabase</span> </span>{\n…\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_1_2 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">1</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</span>\n   }\n};\n…\ndatabase =  Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),\n       UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2)\n       .build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Database</span>(entities = {User.class}, version = <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>)</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"ALTER TABLE users \"</span>\n               + <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\"</span>);\n   }\n};</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),\n       UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)\n       .build();﻿</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">4</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Create the new table</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Copy the data</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Remove the old table</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"DROP TABLE users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Change the table name to the correct one</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\"</span>);\n   }\n};</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">1</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">4</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Create the new table</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\"</span>);\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Copy the data</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Remove the old table</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"DROP TABLE users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Change the table name to the correct one</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\"</span>);\n   }\n};﻿</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),\n       UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)\n       .build();﻿</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link\" href=\"https://github.com/GennextIt/Exp1HelloWorld\">Download Source Code</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Migration','','publish','open','open','','android-room-migration','','\nhttps://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/','2018-12-13 06:52:58','2018-12-13 06:52:58','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/?p=131',0,'post','',0),(132,1,'2018-12-12 06:11:33','2018-12-12 06:11:33','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:11:33','2018-12-12 06:11:33','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(138,1,'2018-12-12 06:39:00','2018-12-12 06:39:00','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>    List&lt;User> getAll();<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>    List&lt;User> loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>           \"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>    User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>    @Insert<br>    void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>    @Delete<br>    void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:39:00','2018-12-12 06:39:00','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(139,1,'2018-12-12 06:39:54','2018-12-12 06:39:54','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:shortcode -->\n@Dao\npublic interface UserDao {\n    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")\n    List<User> getAll();\n\n    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")\n    List<User> loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);\n\n    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +\n           \"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")\n    User findByName(String first, String last);\n\n    @Insert\n    void insertAll(User... users);\n\n    @Delete\n    void delete(User user);\n}\n<!-- /wp:shortcode -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:39:54','2018-12-12 06:39:54','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(142,1,'2018-12-12 06:41:39','2018-12-12 06:41:39','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>@Dao\npublic interface UserDao {\n    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")\n    List&lt;User> getAll();\n\n    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")\n    List&lt;User> loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);\n\n    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +\n           \"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")\n    User findByName(String first, String last);\n\n    @Insert\n    void insertAll(User... users);\n\n    @Delete\n    void delete(User user);\n}</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:41:39','2018-12-12 06:41:39','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(144,1,'2018-12-12 06:42:25','2018-12-12 06:42:25','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:verse -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-verse\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>    List&lt;User> getAll();<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>    List&lt;User> loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>           \"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>    User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>    @Insert<br>    void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>    @Delete<br>    void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:verse -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:42:25','2018-12-12 06:42:25','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(146,1,'2018-12-12 06:44:42','2018-12-12 06:44:42','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Database(entities = {User.class},<strong> </strong>version = 2)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>};</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = &nbsp;Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>.addMigrations(</strong><strong><em>MIGRATION_1_2</em></strong><strong>)</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link\" href=\"https://github.com/GennextIt/Exp1HelloWorld\">Download Source Code</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:44:42','2018-12-12 06:44:42','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(148,1,'2018-12-12 06:48:02','2018-12-12 06:48:02','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;		.build();</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Untitled Reusable Block','','publish','closed','closed','','untitled-reusable-block','','','2018-12-12 06:48:02','2018-12-12 06:48:02','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/untitled-reusable-block/',0,'wp_block','',0),(151,1,'2018-12-12 06:51:15','2018-12-12 06:51:15','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()<br>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")<br>               		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()<br>               		.build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class},version = 2)<br>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>…<br>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {<br>   @Override<br>   public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {<br>       // Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.<br>   }<br>};<br>…<br>database =  Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),<br>       UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")<br>       <strong>.addMigrations(<em>MIGRATION_1_2</em>)</strong><br>       .build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;+ \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Override</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Create the new table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Copy the data</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Remove the old table</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>};</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;.build();</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link\" href=\"https://github.com/GennextIt/Exp1HelloWorld\">Download Source Code</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:51:15','2018-12-12 06:51:15','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(154,1,'2018-12-12 06:58:09','2018-12-12 06:58:09','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()<br>,UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")<br>               		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()<br>               		.build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class},version = 2)<br>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>…<br>static final Migration <em>MIGRATION_1_2 </em>= new Migration(1, 2) {<br>   @Override<br>   public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {<br>       // Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.<br>   }<br>};<br>…<br>database =  Room.<em>databaseBuilder</em>(context.getApplicationContext(),<br>       UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")<br>       <strong>.addMigrations(<em>MIGRATION_1_2</em>)</strong><br>       .build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><em>@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 3)</em></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = new Migration(2, 3) {</em><br><em>   @Override</em><br><em>   public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users \"</em><br><em>               + \" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\");</em><br><em>   }</em><br><em>};</em></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em><br><em>       UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em><br><em>       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)</em><br><em>       .build();</em></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = new Migration(3, 4) {</em><br><em>   @Override</em><br><em>   public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em><br><em>       // Create the new table</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(</em><br><em>               \"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br><br><em>// Copy the data</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(</em><br><em>               \"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br><br><em>// Remove the old table</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br><br><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em><br><em>   }</em><br><em>};</em></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br><em>static final Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = new Migration(1, 4) {</em><br><em>   @Override</em><br><em>   public void migrate(SupportSQLiteDatabase database) {</em><br><em>       // Create the new table</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(</em><br><em>               \"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\");</em><br><em>       // Copy the data</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(</em><br><em>               \"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\");</em><br><br><em>// Remove the old table</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(\"DROP TABLE users\");</em><br><br><em>// Change the table name to the correct one</em><br><em>       database.execSQL(\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\");</em><br><em>   }</em><br><em>};</em></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br><em>database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),</em><br><em>       UsersDatabase.class, \"Sample.db\")</em><br><em>       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)</em><br><em>       .build();</em></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link\" href=\"https://github.com/GennextIt/Exp1HelloWorld\">Download Source Code</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 06:58:09','2018-12-12 06:58:09','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(156,1,'2018-12-12 07:04:32','2018-12-12 07:04:32','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Entity<br>public class User {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @PrimaryKey<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public int uid;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String firstName;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String lastName;<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; getAll();<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Insert<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Delete<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 1)<br>public abstract class AppDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public abstract UserDao userDao();<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AppDatabase.class, \"database-name\").build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)<br>    public void insertUsers(User... users);<br><br>    @Insert<br>    public void insertBothUsers(User user1, User user2);<br><br>    @Insert<br>    public void insertUsersAndFriends(User user, List&lt;User> friends);<br><br>}<br></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Update<br>    public void updateUsers(User... users);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Delete<br>    public void deleteUsers(User... users);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br><br>    public User[] loadAllUsers();<br><br>}<br></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age > :minAge\")<br><br>    public User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(int minAge);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\")<br><br>    public User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(int minAge, int maxAge);<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \" +<br>           \"OR last_name LIKE :search\")<br><br>    public List&lt;User> findUserWithName(String search);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>public class NameTuple {<br><br>    @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>    public String firstName;<br><br>    @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>    public String lastName;<br><br>}<br><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\")<br>    public List&lt;NameTuple> loadFullName();<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")<br><br>    public List&lt;NameTuple> loadUsersFromRegions(List&lt;String> regions);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>app/build.gradle</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>dependencies {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;implementation \'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Flowable&lt;User&gt; loadUserById(int id);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Emits the number of users added to the database.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; insertLargeNumberOfUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Insert</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Completable insertLargeNumberOfUsers(User... users);<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;least one user. */</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Delete</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Single&lt;Integer&gt; deleteUsers(List&lt;User&gt; users);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public Cursor loadRawUsersOlderThan(int minAge);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT * FROM book \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public List&lt;Book&gt; findBooksBorrowedByNameSync(String userName);</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>@Dao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>public interface MyDao {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;@Query(\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"FROM user, pet \" +</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\")</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;public LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;// \"public\" access modifier.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;static class UserPet {</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String userName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public String petName;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> &nbsp;&nbsp;}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>}</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a>&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 07:04:32','2018-12-12 07:04:32','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(158,1,'2018-12-12 07:08:50','2018-12-12 07:08:50','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Entity<br>public class User {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @PrimaryKey<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public int uid;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String firstName;<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public String lastName;<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Dao<br>public interface UserDao {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; getAll();<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; List&lt;User&gt; loadAllByIds(int[] userIds);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \" +<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\")<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; User findByName(String first, String last);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Insert<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void insertAll(User... users);<br><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Delete<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; void delete(User user);<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">@Database(entities = {User.class}, version = 1)<br>public abstract class AppDatabase extends RoomDatabase {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public abstract UserDao userDao();<br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AppDatabase.class, \"database-name\").build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Insert(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)<br>    public void insertUsers(User... users);<br><br>    @Insert<br>    public void insertBothUsers(User user1, User user2);<br><br>    @Insert<br>    public void insertUsersAndFriends(User user, List&lt;User> friends);<br><br>}<br></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Update<br>    public void updateUsers(User... users);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Delete<br>    public void deleteUsers(User... users);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user\")<br><br>    public User[] loadAllUsers();<br><br>}<br></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age > :minAge\")<br><br>    public User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(int minAge);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\")<br><br>    public User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(int minAge, int maxAge);<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \" +<br>           \"OR last_name LIKE :search\")<br><br>    public List&lt;User> findUserWithName(String search);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>public class NameTuple {<br><br>    @ColumnInfo(name = \"first_name\")<br>    public String firstName;<br><br>    @ColumnInfo(name = \"last_name\")<br>    public String lastName;<br><br>}<br><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\")<br>    public List&lt;NameTuple> loadFullName();<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")<br><br>    public List&lt;NameTuple> loadUsersFromRegions(List&lt;String> regions);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\")<br><br>    public LiveData&lt;List&lt;User>> loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String> regions);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">app/build.gradle</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>dependencies {<br><br>    implementation \'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\")<br><br>    public Flowable&lt;User> loadUserById(int id);<br><br>    // Emits the number of users added to the database.<br>    @Insert<br>    public Maybe&lt;Integer> insertLargeNumberOfUsers(List&lt;User> users);<br><br>    // Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.<br>    @Insert<br>    public Completable insertLargeNumberOfUsers(User... users);<br><br>    /* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at<br>       least one user. */<br>    @Delete<br>    public Single&lt;Integer> deleteUsers(List&lt;User> users);<br><br>}<br></pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age > :minAge LIMIT 5\")<br><br>    public Cursor loadRawUsersOlderThan(int minAge);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>    @Query(\"SELECT * FROM book \" +<br>           \"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \" +<br>           \"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \" +<br>           \"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\")<br><br>   public List&lt;Book> findBooksBorrowedByNameSync(String userName);<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\"><br>@Dao<br>public interface MyDao {<br><br>   @Query(\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \" +<br>          \"FROM user, pet \" +<br>          \"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\")<br><br>   public LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet>> loadUserAndPetNames();<br><br>   // You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the<br><br>   // \"public\" access modifier.<br>   static class UserPet {<br>       public String userName;<br>       public String petName;<br>   }<br><br>}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a>&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-12 07:08:50','2018-12-12 07:08:50','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/12/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(192,1,'2018-12-13 06:52:49','2018-12-13 06:52:49','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 1: keep the database version unchanged — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: Room cannot verify the data integrity. Looks like you’ve changed schema but forgot to update the version number. You can simply fix this by increasing the version number.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 2: version increased, but no migration provided — app crashes</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>java.lang.IllegalStateException: A migration from 1 to 2 is necessary. Please provide a Migration in the builder or call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the builder in which case Room will re-create all of the tables.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 3: version increased, fallback to destructive migration enabled — database is cleared</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you don’t want to provide migrations and you specifically <strong>want your database to be cleared</strong> when you upgrade the version, call fallbackToDestructiveMigration in the database builder:<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext()\n,UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n               		.fallbackToDestructiveMigration()\n               		.build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Scenario 4: version increased, migration provided — data is kept</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To keep the user’s data, we need to implement a migration. Since the schema doesn’t change, we just need to provide an <strong>empty migration implementation</strong> and tell Room to use it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Database</span>(entities = {User.class},version = <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>)\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">UsersDatabase</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">RoomDatabase</span> </span>{\n…\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_1_2 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">1</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Since we didn\'t alter the table, there\'s nothing else to do here.</span>\n   }\n};\n…\ndatabase =  Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),\n       UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2)\n       .build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migration with simple schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s add another column: last_update, to our users table, by modifying the User class. In the UsersDatabase class we need to do the following changes:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1. Increase the version to 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Database</span>(entities = {User.class}, version = <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>)</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>public abstract class UsersDatabase extends RoomDatabase</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2. Add a Migration from version 2 to version 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_2_3 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"ALTER TABLE users \"</span>\n               + <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\" ADD COLUMN last_update INTEGER\"</span>);\n   }\n};</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3. Add the migration to the Room database builder:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),\n       UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3)\n       .build();﻿</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Migrations with complex schema changes</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SQLite’s ALTER TABLE… command is <a href=\"https://sqlite.org/lang_altertable.html\">quite limited</a>. For example, changing the id of the user from an int to a String takes several steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>create a new temporary table with the new schema,</li><li>copy the data from the users table to the temporary table,</li><li>drop the users table</li><li>rename the temporary table to users</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using Room, the Migration implementation looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_3_4 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">4</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Create the new table</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Copy the data</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Remove the old table</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"DROP TABLE users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Change the table name to the correct one</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\"</span>);\n   }\n};</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Multiple database version increments</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>What if your users have an old version of your app, running database version 1, and want to upgrade to version 4? So far, we have defined the following migrations: version 1 to 2, version 2 to 3, version 3 to 4, so Room will trigger all migrations, one after another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room can handle more than one version increment: we can define a migration that goes from version 1 to 4 in a single step, making the migration process faster.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> Migration MIGRATION_1_4 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> Migration(<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">1</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">4</span>) {\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">migrate</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(SupportSQLiteDatabase database)</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Create the new table</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"CREATE TABLE users_new (userid TEXT, username TEXT, last_update INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(userid))\"</span>);\n       <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Copy the data</span>\n       database.execSQL(\n               <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INSERT INTO users_new (userid, username, last_update) SELECT userid, username, last_update FROM users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Remove the old table</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"DROP TABLE users\"</span>);\n\n<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Change the table name to the correct one</span>\n       database.execSQL(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"ALTER TABLE users_new RENAME TO users\"</span>);\n   }\n};﻿</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next, we just add it to the list of migrations:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">database = Room.databaseBuilder(context.getApplicationContext(),\n       UsersDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Sample.db\"</span>)\n       .addMigrations(MIGRATION_1_2, MIGRATION_2_3, MIGRATION_3_4, MIGRATION_1_4)\n       .build();﻿</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Note that the queries you write in the </em>Migration.migrate<em> implementation are not compiled at run time, unlike the queries from your DAOs. Make sure that you’re </em><a href=\"https://medium.com/google-developers/testing-room-migrations-be93cdb0d975\"><em>implementing tests for your migrations</em></a><em>.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a></li><li><a href=\"https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929\">https://medium.com/androiddevelopers/understanding-migrations-with-room-f01e04b07929</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/\">https://www.simplifiedcoding.net/android-room-database-example/</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:button -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-button\"><a class=\"wp-block-button__link\" href=\"https://github.com/GennextIt/Exp1HelloWorld\">Download Source Code</a></div>\n<!-- /wp:button -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Migration','','inherit','closed','closed','','131-revision-v1','','','2018-12-13 06:52:49','2018-12-13 06:52:49','',131,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/13/131-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(195,1,'2018-12-13 07:01:13','2018-12-13 07:01:13','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Save data in a local database using Room</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides an abstraction layer over SQLite to allow fluent database access while harnessing the full power of SQLite.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are 3 major components in Room:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><strong>Database:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the database holder and serves as the main access point for the underlying connection to your app\'s persisted, relational data.The class that\'s annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>@Database</code></a>&nbsp;should satisfy the following conditions:<ul><li>Be an abstract class that extends&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>.</li><li>Include the list of entities associated with the database within the annotation.</li><li>Contain an abstract method that has 0 arguments and returns the class that is annotated with&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Dao.html\"><code>@Dao</code></a>.At runtime, you can acquire an instance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Database.html\"><code>Database</code></a>&nbsp;by calling&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#databaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E,%20java.lang.String)\"><code>Room.databaseBuilder()</code></a>&nbsp;or<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Room.html#inMemoryDatabaseBuilder(android.content.Context,%20java.lang.Class%3CT%3E)\"><code>Room.inMemoryDatabaseBuilder()</code></a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Entity:</strong>&nbsp;Represents a table within the database.</li><li><strong>DAO:</strong>&nbsp;Contains the methods used for accessing the database.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The following code snippet contains a sample database configuration with one entity and one DAO:\\</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Entity</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">User</span> </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@PrimaryKey</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> uid;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"first_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String firstName;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"last_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String lastName;\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>UserDao</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">UserDao</span> </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\">List&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">getAll</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE uid IN (:userIds)\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\">List&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadAllByIds</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span>[] userIds)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :first AND \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"last_name LIKE :last LIMIT 1\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\">User <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">findByName</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String first, String last)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertAll</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Delete</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">delete</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User user)</span></span>;\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppDatabase</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Database</span>(entities = {User.class}, version = <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">1</span>)\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">AppDatabase</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">RoomDatabase</span> </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> UserDao <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">userDao</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After creating the files above, you get an instance of the created database using the following code:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">AppDatabase db = Room.databaseBuilder(getApplicationContext(),\n        AppDatabase.class, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"database-name\"</span>).build();</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\"><strong>Note:&nbsp;</strong>If your app runs in a single process, you should follow the singleton design pattern when instantiating an&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;object. Each&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/RoomDatabase.html\"><code>RoomDatabase</code></a>&nbsp;instance is fairly expensive, and you rarely need access to multiple instances within a single process.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"customBackgroundColor\":\"#d9edf9\"} -->\n<p style=\"background-color:#d9edf9\" class=\"has-background\">If your app runs in multiple processes, include&nbsp;<code>enableMultiInstanceInvalidation()</code>&nbsp;in your database builder invocation. That way, when you have an instance of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;in each process, you can invalidate the shared database file in one process, and this invalidation automatically propagates to the instances of&nbsp;<code>AppDatabase</code>&nbsp;within other processes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Database Queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Insert</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you create a DAO method and annotate it with <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Insert.html\">@Insert</a>, Room generates an implementation that inserts all parameters into the database in a single transaction.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>(onConflict = OnConflictStrategy.REPLACE)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertBothUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User user1, User user2)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertUsersAndFriends</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User user, List&lt;User&gt; friends)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Update</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Update.html\">Update</a> convenience method modifies a set of entities, given as parameters, in the database. It uses a query that matches against the primary key of each entity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Update</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">updateUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Delete</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Delete.html\">Delete</a> convenience method removes a set of entities, given as parameters, from the database. It uses the primary keys to find the entities to delete.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Delete</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">deleteUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Query for information</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> is the main annotation used in DAO classes. It allows you to perform read/write operations on a database. Each <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/room/Query.html\">@Query</a> method is verified at compile time, so if there is a problem with the query, a compilation error occurs instead of a runtime failure.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room also verifies the return value of the query such that if the name of the field in the returned object doesn\'t match the corresponding column names in the query response, Room alerts you in one of the following two ways:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>It gives a warning if only some field names match.</li><li>It gives an error if no field names match.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> User[] loadAllUsers();\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing parameters into the query</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> User[] loadAllUsersOlderThan(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> minAge);\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also pass multiple parameters or reference them multiple times in a query, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age BETWEEN :minAge AND :maxAge\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> User[] loadAllUsersBetweenAges(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> minAge, <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> maxAge);\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE first_name LIKE :search \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"OR last_name LIKE :search\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">findUserWithName</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String search)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Returning subsets of columns</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">NameTuple</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"first_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String firstName;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@ColumnInfo</span>(name = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"last_name\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String lastName;\n\n}\n\n<span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;NameTuple&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadFullName</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Passing a collection of arguments</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some of your queries might require you to pass in a variable number of parameters, with the exact number of parameters not known until runtime. For example, you might want to retrieve information about all users from a subset of regions. Room understands when a parameter represents a collection and automatically expands it at runtime based on the number of parameters provided.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;NameTuple&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadUsersFromRegions</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(List&lt;String&gt; regions)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Observable queries</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When performing queries, you\'ll often want your app\'s UI to update automatically when the data changes. To achieve this, use a return value of type <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> in your query method description. Room generates all necessary code to update the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/lifecycle/LiveData.html\">LiveData</a> when the database is updated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT first_name, last_name FROM user WHERE region IN (:regions)\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> LiveData&lt;List&lt;User&gt;&gt; loadUsersFromRegionsSync(List&lt;String&gt; regions);\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Reactive queries with RxJava</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Room provides the following support for return values of RxJava2 types:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>@Query methods: Room supports return values of type <a href=\"http://www.reactive-streams.org/reactive-streams-1.0.1-javadoc/org/reactivestreams/Publisher.html\">Publisher</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Flowable.html\">Flowable</a>, and<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/2.x/javadoc/io/reactivex/Observable.html\">Observable</a>.</li><li>@Insert, @Update, and @Delete methods: Room 2.1.0 and higher supports return values of type<a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Completable.html\">Completable</a>, <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Single.html\">Single&lt;T&gt;</a>, and <a href=\"http://reactivex.io/RxJava/javadoc/io/reactivex/Maybe.html\">Maybe&lt;T&gt;</a>.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To use this functionality, include the latest version of the <strong>rxjava2</strong> artifact in your app\'s build.gradle file:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">app/build.gradle</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">dependencies {\n\n    implementation <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'androidx.room:room-rxjava2:2.1.0-alpha02\'</span>\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * from user where id = :id LIMIT 1\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Flowable&lt;User&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadUserById</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> id)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Emits the number of users added to the database.</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Maybe&lt;Integer&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertLargeNumberOfUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(List&lt;User&gt; users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// Makes sure that the operation finishes successfully.</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Insert</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Completable <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">insertLargeNumberOfUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(User... users)</span></span>;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">/* Emits the number of users removed from the database. Always emits at\n       least one user. */</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Delete</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Single&lt;Integer&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">deleteUsers</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(List&lt;User&gt; users)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Direct cursor access</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If your app\'s logic requires direct access to the return rows, you can return a <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/android/database/Cursor.html\">Cursor</a> object from your queries, as shown in the following code snippet:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM user WHERE age &gt; :minAge LIMIT 5\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> Cursor <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">loadRawUsersOlderThan</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> minAge)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Querying multiple tables</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT * FROM book \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INNER JOIN loan ON loan.book_id = book.id \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"INNER JOIN user ON user.id = loan.user_id \"</span> +\n           <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"WHERE user.name LIKE :userName\"</span>)\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> List&lt;Book&gt; <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">findBooksBorrowedByNameSync</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String userName)</span></span>;\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can also return POJOs from these queries. For example, you can write a query that loads a user and their pet\'s name as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Dao</span>\n<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyDao</span> </span>{\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Query</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"SELECT user.name AS userName, pet.name AS petName \"</span> +\n          <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"FROM user, pet \"</span> +\n          <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"WHERE user.id = pet.user_id\"</span>)\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> LiveData&lt;List&lt;UserPet&gt;&gt; loadUserAndPetNames();\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// You can also define this class in a separate file, as long as you add the</span>\n\n   <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// \"public\" access modifier.</span>\n   <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">UserPet</span> </span>{\n       <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String userName;\n       <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String petName;\n   }\n\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Reference:</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/\">https://developer.android.com/training/data-storage/room/</a>&nbsp;</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Room Database','','inherit','closed','closed','','92-revision-v1','','','2018-12-13 07:01:13','2018-12-13 07:01:13','',92,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/13/92-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(198,1,'2018-12-13 07:37:09','2018-12-13 07:37:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Transitions between activities and fragments in Android involved animating the entire view hierarchy. However, with Material Design, it is now easier to animate selected Views during a transition to emphasize continuity, and guide users to content in the target Activity/Fragment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Shared elements in Activities</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the sample project, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"In the sample project, available on github, we implement two activities, StartActivity and EndActivity.\nThe StartActivity has an ImageView, a Button and a TextView saved in res/layout/activity_start.xml. (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/Droidhelios/SampleSharedElementTransition.git\" target=\"_blank\">available on github</a>, we implement two activities, StartActivity and EndActivity.<br>The StartActivity has an ImageView, a Button and a TextView</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>activity_start.xml.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"php\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">&lt;?</span>xml version=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"1.0\"</span> encoding=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"utf-8\"</span><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">?&gt;</span></span>\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span> <span class=\"hljs-attr\">xmlns:android</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_margin</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"16dp\"</span>&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">ImageView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"120dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"120dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_centerHorizontal</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:src</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@drawable/ic_logo_appsfeature\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:transitionName</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@string/activity_logo_trans\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">TextView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/textView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_below</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:text</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Simple TextView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:textSize</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"20sp\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">Button</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/button\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_below</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/textView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentEnd</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentRight</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:text</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Click Me\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">style</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@style/Widget.AppCompat.Button.Borderless\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:onClick</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"onClick\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;/<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span>&gt;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The EndActivity has two ImageViews and an EditText</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>activity_end.xml.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"php\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">&lt;?</span>xml version=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"1.0\"</span> encoding=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"utf-8\"</span><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">?&gt;</span></span>\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span> <span class=\"hljs-attr\">xmlns:android</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_margin</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"16dp\"</span>&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">ImageView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"220dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"220dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentEnd</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentRight</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentBottom</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:src</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@drawable/ic_logo_appsfeature\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:transitionName</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@string/activity_logo_trans\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">EditText</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/editText\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentStart</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentLeft</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:hint</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"An EditText\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:textSize</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"24sp\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">ImageView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/smallerImageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_toLeftOf</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignBottom</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentStart</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentLeft</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:tint</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@color/colorPrimary\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:src</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@drawable/ic_logo_appsfeature\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;/<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span>&gt;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','Shared element transitions in activities and fragments','','publish','open','open','','shared-element-transitions-in-activities-and-fragments','','','2018-12-13 07:38:03','2018-12-13 07:38:03','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/?p=198',0,'post','',0),(199,1,'2018-12-13 07:37:09','2018-12-13 07:37:09','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Transitions between activities and fragments in Android involved animating the entire view hierarchy. However, with Material Design, it is now easier to animate selected Views during a transition to emphasize continuity, and guide users to content in the target Activity/Fragment.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Shared elements in Activities</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the sample project, <a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\"In the sample project, available on github, we implement two activities, StartActivity and EndActivity.\nThe StartActivity has an ImageView, a Button and a TextView saved in res/layout/activity_start.xml. (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/Droidhelios/SampleSharedElementTransition.git\" target=\"_blank\">available on github</a>, we implement two activities, StartActivity and EndActivity.<br>The StartActivity has an ImageView, a Button and a TextView</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>activity_start.xml.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"php\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">&lt;?</span>xml version=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"1.0\"</span> encoding=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"utf-8\"</span><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">?&gt;</span></span>\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span> <span class=\"hljs-attr\">xmlns:android</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_margin</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"16dp\"</span>&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">ImageView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"120dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"120dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_centerHorizontal</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:src</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@drawable/ic_logo_appsfeature\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:transitionName</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@string/activity_logo_trans\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">TextView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/textView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_below</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:text</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Simple TextView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:textSize</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"20sp\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">Button</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/button\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_below</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/textView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentEnd</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentRight</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:text</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Click Me\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">style</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@style/Widget.AppCompat.Button.Borderless\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:onClick</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"onClick\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;/<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span>&gt;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The EndActivity has two ImageViews and an EditText</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>activity_end.xml.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"php\"><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">&lt;?</span>xml version=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"1.0\"</span> encoding=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"utf-8\"</span><span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">?&gt;</span></span>\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span> <span class=\"hljs-attr\">xmlns:android</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_margin</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"16dp\"</span>&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">ImageView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"220dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"220dp\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentEnd</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentRight</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentBottom</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:src</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@drawable/ic_logo_appsfeature\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:transitionName</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@string/activity_logo_trans\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">EditText</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/editText\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentStart</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentLeft</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:hint</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"An EditText\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:textSize</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"24sp\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">ImageView</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:id</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/smallerImageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_width</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_height</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_toLeftOf</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignBottom</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@id/imageView\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentStart</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:layout_alignParentLeft</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"true\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:tint</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@color/colorPrimary\"</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-attr\">android:src</span>=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@drawable/ic_logo_appsfeature\"</span>/&gt;</span>\n\n<span class=\"hljs-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">&lt;/<span class=\"hljs-name\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">RelativeLayout</span>&gt;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','Shared element transitions in activities and fragments','','inherit','closed','closed','','198-revision-v1','','','2018-12-13 07:37:09','2018-12-13 07:37:09','',198,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2018/12/13/198-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(201,1,'2019-01-05 09:49:51','2019-01-05 09:49:51','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is my newest list of Android libraries, tools and projects which you may find interesting or helpful during your day-to-day work. They are also great for an inspiration or experiments.<br>I hope you will enjoy it. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s start!</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1>TedImagePicker </h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>TedImagePicker is&nbsp;<strong>simple/beautiful/smart</strong>&nbsp;image picker</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Support Image/Video</li><li>Support Single/Multi select</li><li>Support more configuration option</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/ParkSangGwon/TedImagePicker\">https://github.com/ParkSangGwon/TedImagePicker</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div align=\"center\"><img src=\"/ParkSangGwon/TedImagePicker/raw/master/art/multi_select.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"max-width:100%;\"></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Showcase View</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/ECLaboratorio/BubbleShowCase-Android.git\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/ECLaboratorio/BubbleShowCase-Android.git</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/mreram/ShowCaseView.git\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/mreram/ShowCaseView.git</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7357\">EasyFlipViewPager</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/wajahatkarim3/EasyFlipViewPager\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/wajahatkarim3/EasyFlipViewPager</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div align=\"center\"><a href=\"https://github.com/ParkSangGwon/TedImagePicker/raw/master/art/multi_select.png?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7697\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ParkSangGwon/TedImagePicker/master/art/multi_select.png\"></a>\n \n</div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7359\">Hauler</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Hauler is a library containing custom layout which enables to easily create swipe to dismiss&nbsp;<code>Activity</code>. Implementation is based on code from project&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/nickbutcher/plaid?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7359\" target=\"_blank\">Plaid</a>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/thefuntasty/hauler\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/thefuntasty/hauler</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/thefuntasty/hauler/master/images/example.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7362\">Easy CSV</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Creates csv file for android </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/hsmnzaydn/easy-csv\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/hsmnzaydn/easy-csv</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7364\">Text Scanner from image</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> This library extend&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developers.google.com/vision/?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7364\" target=\"_blank\">google vision</a>&nbsp;. And initilay it read text from image. for reading text from image you have to give image&nbsp;<strong>Uri</strong>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<strong>Bitmap</strong>. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/mahimrocky/TextRecognizer\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/mahimrocky/TextRecognizer</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mahimrocky/TextRecognizer/master/screenshot.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7366\">Choreographer</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Animate views easily by chaining animations, run them serially or in parallel. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/ZachBublil/Choreographer\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/ZachBublil/Choreographer</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ZachBublil/Choreographer/master/demoGif.gif\" alt=\"\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7367\">BottomSheetTimeRangePicker</a></h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BottomSheetPickers is a tiny Android library for adding Date and Time Pickers as Modal BottomSheetDialogs with From and To ranges.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The library is inspired by Titto Jose\'s&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/tittojose/TimeRangePicker?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7367\" target=\"_blank\">TimeRangePicker</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/adawoud/BottomSheetTimeRangePicker\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/adawoud/BottomSheetTimeRangePicker</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/adawoud/BottomSheetTimeRangePicker/master/art/bottomsheetpicker.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7376\">android-imagecropview</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> An Android library that lets you implement image crop. ImageCropView crops image by moving image under fixed crop area like instagram and iOS. Image zoom in/out is base on&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/sephiroth74/ImageViewZoom?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7376\" target=\"_blank\">sephiroth74\'s imageViewZoom. Sample app is base on&nbsp;</a><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developers.aviary.com/?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7376\" target=\"_blank\">aviary SDK sample.</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/naver/android-imagecropview\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/naver/android-imagecropview</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/naver/android-imagecropview/master/doc/img/pholar.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7417\">Payment Card View</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/manojbhadane/PaymentCardView\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/manojbhadane/PaymentCardView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/manojbhadane/PaymentCardView/master/PaymentCardView.png\" alt=\"\"/><figcaption><br></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7407\">Dynamic Toasts</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/hotstu/ZebraTextView\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/hotstu/ZebraTextView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> A simple library to display themed toasts with icon and text on Android 9+ (Gingerbread or above) devices. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pranavpandey/dynamic-toasts/master/graphics/dynamic-toasts-preview.png\" alt=\"\"/><figcaption><br></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7401\">Material Toast</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/marcoscgdev/MaterialToast\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/marcoscgdev/MaterialToast</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nA fully and highly customizable material designed Toast for Android.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marcoscgdev/MaterialToast/master/device-2018-12-22-164932.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7351\">StateViews</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/kobeumut/StateViews\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/kobeumut/StateViews</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Create &amp; Show progress, data or error views, the easy way! </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kobeumut/StateViews/master/art/StatusPage.jpg\" alt=\"\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7334\">Country code dialog picker</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://github.com/BartNijland91/android-countrycodepickerdialog\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/BartNijland91/android-countrycodepickerdialog</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BartNijland91/android-countrycodepickerdialog/master/screenshot.png\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7340\">Cyanea</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/jaredrummler/Cyanea\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/jaredrummler/Cyanea</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nA powerful, dynamic, and fun theme engine. Named after Octopus Cyanea which is adept at camouflage and not only can change color frequently, but also can change the patterns on and texture of its skin.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\">\n<a>\n<img src=\"https://camo.githubusercontent.com/7f7f7520d61f2f704ff12d6d31b7cafe601263e4/68747470733a2f2f692e696d6775722e636f6d2f6543366435574f2e676966\" alt=\"\">\n</a>\n<a>\n<img align=\"left\" hspace=\"10\" src=\"https://camo.githubusercontent.com/b0cdc1242d8170b8184ef2a92d8afd5af4152563/68747470733a2f2f692e696d6775722e636f6d2f706a44456a576c2e676966\">\n</a>\n</figure> \n</div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/3/7342\">CurvedBottomNavigationView</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/androidtutorialonline/CurvedBottomNavigationView\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/androidtutorialonline/CurvedBottomNavigationView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nwe will learn How to draw custom shapes in Curved Bottom Navigation View\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://camo.githubusercontent.com/7cf1dee61362f29a0abd06248d8b439a5323130f/68747470733a2f2f7777772e616e64726f69647475746f7269616c6f6e6c696e652e636f6d2f77702d636f6e74656e742f75706c6f6164732f323031382f31312f426f74746f6d4e617669676174696f6e566965772e676966\" alt=\"enter image description here\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7350\">FloatingToast</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/hariprasanths/FloatingToast\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/hariprasanths/FloatingToast</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nAn android library to make customisable floating animated toasts\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://camo.githubusercontent.com/b469bd7e9f684420b89eab81e7c91fecd6c9831d/68747470733a2f2f6d656469612e67697068792e636f6d2f6d656469612f5a784c624c76557434394f3057744c4575662f67697068792e676966\" alt=\"\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7306\">Hidden SearchView in RecyclerView</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/lnicolet/HiddenSearchWithRecyclerView\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/lnicolet/HiddenSearchWithRecyclerView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> An easy way to search in your recycler view without having an always-on display search view. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/lnicolet/HiddenSearchWithRecyclerView/master/default_example.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7316\">SMS view</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/VRGsoftUA/SmsView\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/VRGsoftUA/SmsView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/VRGsoftUA/SmsView/master/preview.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7320\">CameraViewEx</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/pvasa/cameraview-ex\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/pvasa/cameraview-ex</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nCameraViewEx makes integration of camera implementation and various camera features into any Android project very easy.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nCameraViewEx requires minimum API level 14. The library uses Camera1 API on API Level 14-20 and Camera2 on API level 21 and above.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7292\">Android Scratchcard</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/myinnos/AndroidScratchCard\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/myinnos/AndroidScratchCard</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nLight Weighted Scratchcard View Library for Android\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/myinnos/AndroidScratchCard/master/images-gif/androidscratchcard-example.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7278\">AndroidVeil</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/skydoves/AndroidVeil\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/skydoves/AndroidVeil</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A library that lets you implement skeletons and shimmer animation for veiling layouts and recyclerView.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\">\n\n<p><a href=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24237865/47777293-c736d780-dd37-11e8-9107-5242746a7b8c.gif?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7278\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24237865/47777293-c736d780-dd37-11e8-9107-5242746a7b8c.gif\" hspace=\"20\"></a> <a href=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24237865/47781860-1aae2300-dd42-11e8-8c5c-a2417b03b74d.gif?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7278\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24237865/47781860-1aae2300-dd42-11e8-8c5c-a2417b03b74d.gif\"></a></p>\n\n</figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7281\">ParallaxView</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/VRGsoftUA/ParallaxView\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/VRGsoftUA/ParallaxView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nView container which applies parallax effect to its content. You can Even achieve 3d effect if you use two containers, one atop another like on video below.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\">\n<a href=\"https://github.com/VRGsoftUA/ParallaxView/blob/master/scroll1.gif?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7281\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"></a><a href=\"https://github.com/VRGsoftUA/ParallaxView/blob/master/scroll2.gif?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7281\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img width=\"270\" height=\"480\" hspace=\"20\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/VRGsoftUA/ParallaxView/master/scroll2.gif\"></a><img width=\"270\" height=\"480\" src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/VRGsoftUA/ParallaxView/master/scroll1.gif\"><br><br> \n\n</figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7282\">WP7ProgressBar</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/shadowalker77/wp7progressbar\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/shadowalker77/wp7progressbar</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nThis library aims to bring awesome windows phone 7 and windows 10 progress bar to android applications. Here is the example:\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/shadowalker77/wp7progressbar/master/ScreenShots/wp10.gif\" alt=\"\" hspace=\"20\">\n<img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/shadowalker77/wp7progressbar/master/ScreenShots/wp7.gif\">\n</figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7287\">SimpleSearchView</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/Ferfalk/SimpleSearchView\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/Ferfalk/SimpleSearchView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A simple SearchView for Android based on Material Design</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>API 16+&nbsp;<em>(Reveal animation for API 21 and above, fade animation otherwise)</em></li><li>Two styles</li><li>Option to hide TabLayout automatically when it opens</li><li>Text and animations listeners</li><li>Customization options</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\">\n<p><a href=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13675455/46987845-4091c180-d0cc-11e8-8904-87f3c24d4c0a.gif?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7287\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img width=\"360\" height=\"600\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13675455/46987845-4091c180-d0cc-11e8-8904-87f3c24d4c0a.gif\"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13675455/46987873-60c18080-d0cc-11e8-8d10-2b8cf8a4124b.gif?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7287\" rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\"><img width=\"360\" height=\"600\" src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13675455/46987873-60c18080-d0cc-11e8-8d10-2b8cf8a4124b.gif\"></a></p>\n</figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7240\">Andrutil</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/ShabanKamell/andrutil\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/ShabanKamell/andrutil</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5>Useful Android Utilities.</h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Available Utils:</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>ActivityUtil\nAppUtil\nBackStackUtil\nBottomNavigationViewUtil\nCallback\nDateUtil\nDiskStorageUtil\nFragmentManagerUtil\nFunc\nGsonUtil\nHtmlUtil\nKeyboardUtil\nKeyguardManagerUtil\nLocaleUtil\nMediaPlayerUtil\nObservableUtil\nPackageInfoUtil\nPhoneUtil\nRecyclerViewUtil\nRtlConfigUtil\nServiceUtil\nSpaceItemDecoration\nSystemOverlayUtil\nToastUtil\nWindowUtil\nVectorDrawableUtil\nDrawableUtil</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7244\">DotLoadersPack</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/agrawalsuneet/DotLoadersPack-Android\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/agrawalsuneet/DotLoadersPack-Android</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12999622/39367184-f3bb706a-4a2d-11e8-9120-5027bbef2861.gif\" alt=\"\" hspace=\"20\">\n\n<img src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12999622/36224573-f274b956-11bf-11e8-8f97-e4c031959465.gif\">\n</figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7248\">EasyAbout</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/marcoscgdev/EasyAbout\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/marcoscgdev/EasyAbout</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nA fully material-designed about fragment for your application.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marcoscgdev/EasyAbout/master/screenshots/1.png\" alt=\"Sample App\" style=\"max-width:25%;\">\n \n<img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marcoscgdev/EasyAbout/master/screenshots/2.png\" alt=\"Sample App\" style=\"max-width:25%;\" hspace=\"20\">\n \n<img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/marcoscgdev/EasyAbout/master/screenshots/3.png\" alt=\"Sample App\" style=\"max-width:25%;\">\n\n</figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7057\">ScatterImageView</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/SIMMORSAL/ScatterImageView\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/SIMMORSAL/ScatterImageView</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nA library that scatters some ImageViews around haphazardly, or orderly\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24822099/42732838-5a9cd2b8-883d-11e8-8463-aefee1f2be11.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"max-width:100%;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7058\">ReadMoreOption</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/devendroid/ReadMoreOption\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/devendroid/ReadMoreOption</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\n\nConvert your TextView in ExpandableTextView with added options ReadMore/ReadLess.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/devendroid/ReadMoreOption/master/assets/rmo-1.0.0.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"max-width:100%;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/6996\">TypeWriterView</a></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://github.com/skymansandy/typewriterview/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://github.com/skymansandy/typewriterview/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>A simple Android library for typewriter like effects</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Features:</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Animate contents of textview as if it were typed by a TypeWriter</li><li>Set Animation Text appearance duration</li><li>Set TypeWriter sound effect (With or without sound)</li><li>Set Typing animation listeners (4 available)</li><li>Set all the usual attributes of TextView and style your view.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter\"><img src=\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/skymansandy/typewriterview/master/art/demoTypeWriterView.gif\" alt=\"\" style=\"width:300px;\"></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Github Important Links:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/mmoamenn/AnimationsPlus?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7251\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/mmoamenn/AnimationsPlus</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/david-serrano/locationprovider?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7231\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/david-serrano/locationprovider</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/GeorgeArgyrakis/Watermark?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7222\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/GeorgeArgyrakis/Watermark</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/Piashsarker/AndroidEasyUtils?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7227\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/Piashsarker/AndroidEasyUtils</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/mohammadatif/Animatoo?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7206\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/mohammadatif/