"https://github.com/jaiselrahman/FilePicker?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7002\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/jaiselrahman/FilePicker</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/shagiz/AsyncFilePicker?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7011\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/shagiz/AsyncFilePicker</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/siralam/BSImagePicker?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6925\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/siralam/BSImagePicker</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/akshay2211/PixImagePicker?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6935\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/akshay2211/PixImagePicker</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/nihad92/SwipeableCards?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6889\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/nihad92/SwipeableCards</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/dipanshukr/Viewpager-Transformation?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6850\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/dipanshukr/Viewpager-Transformation</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/WindSekirun/SectionCalendarView?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6807\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/WindSekirun/SectionCalendarView</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/Team-Blox/TreeView?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6779\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/Team-Blox/TreeView</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/Angads25/android-toggle?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6778\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/Angads25/android-toggle</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/florent37/ShapeOfView?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6782\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/florent37/ShapeOfView</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"http://github.com/mreram/TicketView?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6799\" target=\"_blank\">http://github.com/mreram/TicketView</a></li><li><a href=\"https://github.com/kevalpatel2106/android-hidden-camera\">https://github.com/kevalpatel2106/android-hidden-camera</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/levitnudi/LegacyTableView?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6819\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/levitnudi/LegacyTableView</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/jkennethcarino/RTextEditorView?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=6207\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/jkennethcarino/RTextEditorView</a></li><li><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://github.com/m7mdra/HtmlRecycler?utm_source=android-arsenal.com&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_campaign=7092\" target=\"_blank\">https://github.com/m7mdra/HtmlRecycler</a></li><li><a href=\"https://github.com/airbnb/lottie-android\">https://github.com/airbnb/lottie-android</a></li><li><a href=\"https://github.com/Blankj/AndroidUtilCode\">https://github.com/Blankj/AndroidUtilCode</a></li><li><a href=\"https://github.com/orhanobut/logger\">https://github.com/orhanobut/logger</a></li><li> <a href=\"https://github.com/iamporus/TypedTextView\">https://github.com/iamporus/TypedTextView</a> </li><li> <a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7687\">https://android-arsenal.com/details/1/7687</a> </li><li> <a href=\"https://github.com/bkhezry/weather\">https://github.com/bkhezry/weather</a> </li><li></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Refrence: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\" href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/\" target=\"_blank\">https://android-arsenal.com/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://android-arsenal.com/?page=21&amp;sort=created\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" aria-label=\" (opens in a new tab)\">https://android-arsenal.com/?page=21&amp;sort=created</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Libs And Tools','','inherit','closed','closed','','201-revision-v1','','','2019-06-21 13:47:48','2019-06-21 12:47:48','',201,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/06/21/201-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(415,1,'2019-07-06 06:11:15','2019-07-06 05:11:15','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Java Generics</strong>&nbsp;programming is introduced in J2SE 5 to deal with type-safe objects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before generics, we can store any type of objects in collection i.e. non-generic. Now generics, forces the java programmer to store specific type of objects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Advantage of Java Generics</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are mainly 3 advantages of generics. They are as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1)	Type-safety :</strong>&nbsp;We can hold only a single type of objects in generics. It doesn’t allow to store other objects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2)	Type casting is not required:</strong>&nbsp;There is no need to typecast the object.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Generic class</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> A class that can refer to any type is known as generic class. Here, we are using&nbsp;<strong>T</strong>&nbsp;type parameter to create the generic class of specific type. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    MyGen&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; myGen = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> MyGen&lt;&gt;();\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//Add data</span>\n    myGen.add(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"data\"</span>);\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//get data</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> output = myGen.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">get</span>();\n     \n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyGen</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">T</span>&gt; </span>{\n        T obj;\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> add(T obj) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span>.obj = obj;\n        }\n\n        T <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">get</span>() {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> obj;\n        }\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Type Parameters</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The type parameters naming conventions are important to learn generics thoroughly. The commonly type parameters are as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>T - Type</li><li>E - Element</li><li>K - Key</li><li>N - Number</li><li>V - Value</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Generic Method</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like generic class, we can create generic method that can accept any type of argument.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s see a simple example of java generic method to print array elements. We are using here&nbsp;<strong>E</strong>&nbsp;to denote the element.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">TestGenerics4</span>{  \n  \n   <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> &lt; E &gt; <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">printArray</span>(<span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">E[] elements</span>) </span>{  \n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">for</span> ( E element : elements){          \n            System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println(element );  \n         }  \n         System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println();  \n    }  \n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">main</span>(<span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\"> String args[] </span>) </span>{  \n        Integer[] intArray = { <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">20</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">30</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">40</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">50</span> };  \n        Character[] charArray = { <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'J\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'A\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'V\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'A\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'T\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'P\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'O\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'I\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'N\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'T\'</span> };  \n  \n        System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println( <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Printing Integer Array\"</span> );  \n        printArray( intArray  );   \n  \n       System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println( <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Printing Character Array\"</span> );  \n        printArray( charArray );   \n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Wildcard in Java Generics</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The ? (question mark) symbol represents wildcard element. It means any type. If we write &lt;? extends Number&gt;, it means any child class of Number e.g. Integer, Float, double etc. Now we can call the method of Number class through any child class object.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let\'s understand it by the example given below:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Shape</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> void draw();\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Rectangle</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Shape</span> </span>{\n        void draw() {\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">System</span>.out.println(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"drawing rectangle\"</span>);\n        }\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Circle</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Shape</span> </span>{\n        void draw() {\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">System</span>.out.println(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"drawing circle\"</span>);\n        }\n    }\n\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">GenericTest</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//creating a method that accepts only child class of Shape  </span>\n        public static void drawShapes(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;? <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Shape</span>&gt; lists) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">for</span> (<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Shape</span> s : lists) {\n                s.draw();<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//calling method of Shape class by child class instance  </span>\n            }\n        }\n\n        public static void main(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> args[]) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Rectangle</span>&gt; list1 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">ArrayList</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Rectangle</span>&gt;();\n            list1.add(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Rectangle</span>());\n\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>&gt; list2 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">ArrayList</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>&gt;();\n            list2.add(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>());\n            list2.add(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>());\n\n            drawShapes(list1);\n            drawShapes(list2);\n        }\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Example 1</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> interface Callback&lt;T&gt; {\n        <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onSuccess(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;T&gt; response);\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onError(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> error);\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> GenericTypeExample() {\n        backgroundJob(<span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">new</span> Callback&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt;() {\n            @Override\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onSuccess(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; response) {\n                <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">Log</span>.e(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"onSuccess\"</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"List size\"</span> + response.size());\n            }\n\n            @Override\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onError(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> error) {\n                <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">Log</span>.e(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"onError\"</span>, error);\n            }\n        });\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> backgroundJob(Callback&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; callback) {\n        <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">list</span> = getList();\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">list</span> != <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">null</span>) {\n            callback.onSuccess(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">list</span>);\n        } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">else</span> {\n            callback.onError(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Empty List\"</span>);\n        }\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> &lt;T&gt; <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;T&gt; getList() {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">new</span> ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n    }\n\n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Example 2</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Service</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">T</span>&gt; </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-function\">T <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">execute</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">FooService</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">implements</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Service</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">String</span>&gt; </span>{\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> String input1;\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> input2;\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">FooService</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String input1, <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> input2)</span> </span>{\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span>.input1 = input1;\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span>.input2 = input2;\n        }\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">execute</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span> </span>{\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> String.format(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"\'%s%d\'\"</span>, input1, input2);\n        }\n    }\n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Example 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> main(View rootView){\n        TextView tvProfile = getViewFromId(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"tv_profile\"</span>, TextView.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span>, rootView);\n        ImageView ivProfile = getViewFromId(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"iv_profile\"</span>, ImageView.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span>, rootView);\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> &lt;T&gt; T getViewFromId(String resourceName, Class&lt;T&gt; <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">type</span>, <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">View</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">rootView</span>) {</span>\n        T t = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">null</span>;\n        int resourceId = getDynamicId(resourceName);\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (resourceId != <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span> &amp;&amp; rootView != <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">null</span>) {\n            t = <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">type</span>.<span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">cast</span></span>(rootView.findViewById(resourceId));\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> t;\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> int getDynamicId(String id) {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> getResources().getIdentifier(id, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"id\"</span>, getPackageName());\n        } catch (Exception e) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>;\n        }\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','Generics in Java','','inherit','closed','closed','','316-revision-v1','','','2019-07-06 06:11:15','2019-07-06 05:11:15','',316,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/06/316-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(417,1,'2019-07-06 07:04:45','2019-07-06 06:04:45','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Java Generics</strong>&nbsp;programming is introduced in J2SE 5 to deal with type-safe objects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before generics, we can store any type of objects in collection i.e. non-generic. Now generics, forces the java programmer to store specific type of objects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Advantage of Java Generics</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are mainly 3 advantages of generics. They are as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1)	Type-safety :</strong>&nbsp;We can hold only a single type of objects in generics. It doesn’t allow to store other objects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2)	Type casting is not required:</strong>&nbsp;There is no need to typecast the object.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Generic class</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> A class that can refer to any type is known as generic class. Here, we are using&nbsp;<strong>T</strong>&nbsp;type parameter to create the generic class of specific type. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    MyGen&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; myGen = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> MyGen&lt;&gt;();\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//Add data</span>\n    myGen.add(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"data\"</span>);\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//get data</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> output = myGen.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">get</span>();\n     \n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyGen</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">T</span>&gt; </span>{\n        T obj;\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> add(T obj) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span>.obj = obj;\n        }\n\n        T <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">get</span>() {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> obj;\n        }\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Type Parameters</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The type parameters naming conventions are important to learn generics thoroughly. The commonly type parameters are as follows:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>T - Type</li><li>E - Element</li><li>K - Key</li><li>N - Number</li><li>V - Value</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Generic Method</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like generic class, we can create generic method that can accept any type of argument.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let’s see a simple example of java generic method to print array elements. We are using here&nbsp;<strong>E</strong>&nbsp;to denote the element.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">TestGenerics4</span>{  \n  \n   <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> &lt; E &gt; <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">printArray</span>(<span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">E[] elements</span>) </span>{  \n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">for</span> ( E element : elements){          \n            System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println(element );  \n         }  \n         System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println();  \n    }  \n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">main</span>(<span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\"> String args[] </span>) </span>{  \n        Integer[] intArray = { <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">20</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">30</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">40</span>, <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">50</span> };  \n        Character[] charArray = { <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'J\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'A\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'V\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'A\'</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'T\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'P\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'O\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'I\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'N\'</span>,<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'T\'</span> };  \n  \n        System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println( <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Printing Integer Array\"</span> );  \n        printArray( intArray  );   \n  \n       System.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">out</span>.println( <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Printing Character Array\"</span> );  \n        printArray( charArray );   \n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Wildcard in Java Generics</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The ? (question mark) symbol represents wildcard element. It means any type. If we write &lt;? extends Number&gt;, it means any child class of Number e.g. Integer, Float, double etc. Now we can call the method of Number class through any child class object.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let\'s understand it by the example given below:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Shape</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">abstract</span> void draw();\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Rectangle</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Shape</span> </span>{\n        void draw() {\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">System</span>.out.println(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"drawing rectangle\"</span>);\n        }\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Circle</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Shape</span> </span>{\n        void draw() {\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">System</span>.out.println(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"drawing circle\"</span>);\n        }\n    }\n\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">GenericTest</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//creating a method that accepts only child class of Shape  </span>\n        public static void drawShapes(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;? <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Shape</span>&gt; lists) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">for</span> (<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Shape</span> s : lists) {\n                s.draw();<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">//calling method of Shape class by child class instance  </span>\n            }\n        }\n\n        public static void main(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> args[]) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Rectangle</span>&gt; list1 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">ArrayList</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Rectangle</span>&gt;();\n            list1.add(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Rectangle</span>());\n\n            <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>&gt; list2 = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">ArrayList</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>&gt;();\n            list2.add(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>());\n            list2.add(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Circle</span>());\n\n            drawShapes(list1);\n            drawShapes(list2);\n        }\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Example 1</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> interface Callback&lt;T&gt; {\n        <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onSuccess(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;T&gt; response);\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onError(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> error);\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> GenericTypeExample() {\n        backgroundJob(<span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">new</span> Callback&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt;() {\n            @Override\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onSuccess(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; response) {\n                <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">Log</span>.e(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"onSuccess\"</span>, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"List size\"</span> + response.size());\n            }\n\n            @Override\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> onError(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span> error) {\n                <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">Log</span>.e(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"onError\"</span>, error);\n            }\n        });\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">void</span> backgroundJob(Callback&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; callback) {\n        <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">String</span>&gt; <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">list</span> = getList();\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">list</span> != <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">null</span>) {\n            callback.onSuccess(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">list</span>);\n        } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">else</span> {\n            callback.onError(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"Empty List\"</span>);\n        }\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> &lt;T&gt; <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">List</span>&lt;T&gt; getList() {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">new</span> ArrayList&lt;&gt;();\n    }\n\n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Example 2</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">interface</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Service</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">T</span>&gt; </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-function\">T <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">execute</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>;\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">FooService</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">implements</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Service</span>&lt;<span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">String</span>&gt; </span>{\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> String input1;\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">final</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> input2;\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">FooService</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String input1, <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> input2)</span> </span>{\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span>.input1 = input1;\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span>.input2 = input2;\n        }\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> String <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">execute</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span> </span>{\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> String.format(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"\'%s%d\'\"</span>, input1, input2);\n        }\n    }\n</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Example 3</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">void</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">main</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span></span>{\n        TextView tvProfile = getViewFromId(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"tv_profile\"</span>, TextView.class, getActivityRootView());\n        ImageView ivProfile = getViewFromId(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"iv_profile\"</span>, ImageView.class, getActivityRootView());\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> &lt;T&gt; <span class=\"hljs-function\">T <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">getViewFromId</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String resourceName, Class&lt;T&gt; type, View rootView)</span> </span>{\n        T t = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">null</span>;\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> resourceId = getDynamicId(resourceName);\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (resourceId != <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span> &amp;&amp; rootView != <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">null</span>) {\n            t = type.cast(rootView.findViewById(resourceId));\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> t;\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">int</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">getDynamicId</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">(String id)</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> getResources().getIdentifier(id, <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"id\"</span>, getPackageName());\n        } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (Exception e) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> <span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>;\n        }\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">public</span> View <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">getActivityRootView</span><span class=\"hljs-params\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">()</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">return</span> getWindow().getDecorView().getRootView();\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','Generics in Java','','inherit','closed','closed','','316-revision-v1','','','2019-07-06 07:04:45','2019-07-06 06:04:45','',316,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/06/316-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(419,1,'2019-07-06 08:09:49','2019-07-06 07:09:49','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Clear cache</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Cache directory Path :</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> C:\\Users\\&lt;username>\\.AndroidStudio3.4\\system\\caches</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":401} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/image.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-401\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Delete cache folder</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Studio','','inherit','closed','closed','','400-revision-v1','','','2019-07-06 08:09:49','2019-07-06 07:09:49','',400,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/06/400-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(421,1,'2019-07-17 06:56:28','2019-07-17 05:56:28','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Implementation Vs Api in Android&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dependencies appearing in the&nbsp;<code>api</code>&nbsp;configurations will be transitively exposed to consumers of the library, and as such will appear on the compile classpath of consumers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dependencies found in the&nbsp;<code>implementation</code>&nbsp;configuration will, on the other hand, not be exposed to consumers, and therefore not leak into the consumers\' compile classpath. This comes with several benefits:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://medium.com/mindorks/implementation-vs-api-in-gradle-3-0-494c817a6fa\">https://medium.com/mindorks/implementation-vs-api-in-gradle-3-0-494c817a6fa</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Calling startActivity() from outside of an Activity exception</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">    android.util.AndroidRuntimeException:</span> Calling startActivity() from outside of\n        an Activity  <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span> requires the FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK flag. Is this\n        really what you want?\n    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">at</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">android.app.ContextImpl.startActivity(ContextImpl.java:912)\n</span>\n    Solution :\n    Intent intent = new Intent(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>, YourActivity.class)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span>\n    intent.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);\n</span>    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>.startActivity(intent)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"20a4\">Making a singleton class for Library</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>A singleton class is a class which can create only an object that can be shared all other classes.</em></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; padding: 0.5em; background: rgb(240, 240, 240); color: rgb(68, 68, 68);\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;\">SingletonClass</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">implements</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;\">Serializable</span> </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">/* Step 4: Use volatile keyword to ensure that the Singleton is thread safe. \n     * The value of a volatile variable will never be stored in the cache. All read and write will be done from and to the main memory.*/</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">static</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">volatile</span> SingletonClass sSoleInstance;\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">/*  Step 1: Make the constructor of the class as \'private\'. \n        This ensures that other classes are not able to create \n        a new instance of the Singleton class.  */</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">private</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;\">SingletonClass</span><span class=\"hljs-params\">()</span></span>{\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">/*  Step 3: Ensure that the Singleton class is Reflection Proof. \n            A new instance of the Singleton can be created using Java Reflection API. \n            In order to prevent that, we need to add a check to the constructor. \n            If the constructor is already initialized, throw a run-time exception.  */</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">if</span> (sSoleInstance != <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">null</span>){\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">new</span> RuntimeException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 0, 0);\">\"Use getInstance() method to get the single instance of this class.\"</span>);\n        }\n    }\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">/*   \n     * Step 2: Create one public static method to provide a single entry point to create a new instance of the class. \n     * Check if a new instance of the class is available. If not, create a new instance of the class.\n     */</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">public</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">static</span> SingletonClass <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;\">getInstance</span><span class=\"hljs-params\">()</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">if</span> (sSoleInstance == <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">null</span>) {\n        \n            <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">/* Step 4: Use Double Check locking method. This means make the Singleton class in the synchronized block \n            only if the instance is null. So, the synchronized block will be executed only when the \'instance\' is null \n            and prevent unnecessary synchronization once the instance variable is initialized.  */</span>\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">synchronized</span> (SingletonClass.class) {\n                <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">if</span> (sSoleInstance == <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">null</span>) sSoleInstance = <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">new</span> SingletonClass();\n            }\n        }\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">return</span> sSoleInstance;\n    }\n\n\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">// Step 5: Ensure that the Singleton class is safe from Serialization. When we need to implement </span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">// Serializable interface in a Singleton class, we need to ensure that the instance is maintained </span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">// before and after serialization. By default when deserialized, a new instance of the Singleton class will be created. </span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">// To prevent creation of another instance, implementat this method. </span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">// This method replaces the object read from the stream and ensures that nobody can create another </span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 136, 136);\">// instance by serializing and deserializing the singleton.</span>\n    <span class=\"hljs-function\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">protected</span> SingletonClass <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(136, 0, 0); font-weight: 700;\">readResolve</span><span class=\"hljs-params\">()</span> </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"font-weight: 700;\">return</span> getInstance();\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','Keep these things in mind for making library','','publish','open','open','','keep-these-things-in-mind-for-making-library','','','2019-11-04 06:20:07','2019-11-04 06:20:07','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/?p=421',0,'post','',0),(422,1,'2019-07-17 06:56:28','2019-07-17 05:56:28','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Common Exception</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.util</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.AndroidRuntimeException</span>: <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">Calling</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">startActivity</span>() <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">from</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">outside</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">of</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">an</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">Activity</span>  <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">context</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">requires</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">the</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">flag</span>. <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">Is</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span> \n        <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">really</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">what</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">you</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">want</span>?\n    <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">at</span> <span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.app</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.ContextImpl</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.startActivity</span>(<span class=\"hljs-selector-tag\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ContextImpl</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.java</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-pseudo\">:912)</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->','Keep these things in mind for making library','','inherit','closed','closed','','421-revision-v1','','','2019-07-17 06:56:28','2019-07-17 05:56:28','',421,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/17/421-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(424,1,'2019-07-17 07:02:39','2019-07-17 06:02:39','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Common Exception</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">    android.util.AndroidRuntimeException:</span> Calling startActivity() from outside of\n        an Activity  <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span> requires the FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK flag. Is this\n        really what you want?\n    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">at</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">android.app.ContextImpl.startActivity(ContextImpl.java:912)\n</span>\n    Solution :\n    Intent intent = new Intent(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>, YourActivity.class)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span>\n    intent.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);\n</span>    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>.startActivity(intent)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Keep these things in mind for making library','','inherit','closed','closed','','421-revision-v1','','','2019-07-17 07:02:39','2019-07-17 06:02:39','',421,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/17/421-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(426,1,'2019-07-17 07:09:57','2019-07-17 06:09:57','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Calling startActivity() from outside of an Activity exception</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">    android.util.AndroidRuntimeException:</span> Calling startActivity() from outside of\n        an Activity  <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span> requires the FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK flag. Is this\n        really what you want?\n    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">at</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">android.app.ContextImpl.startActivity(ContextImpl.java:912)\n</span>\n    Solution :\n    Intent intent = new Intent(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>, YourActivity.class)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span>\n    intent.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);\n</span>    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>.startActivity(intent)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Keep these things in mind for making library','','inherit','closed','closed','','421-revision-v1','','','2019-07-17 07:09:57','2019-07-17 06:09:57','',421,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/17/421-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(428,1,'2019-07-22 10:49:46','2019-07-22 09:49:46','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Implementation Vs Api in Android </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dependencies appearing in the&nbsp;<code>api</code>&nbsp;configurations will be transitively exposed to consumers of the library, and as such will appear on the compile classpath of consumers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dependencies found in the&nbsp;<code>implementation</code>&nbsp;configuration will, on the other hand, not be exposed to consumers, and therefore not leak into the consumers\' compile classpath. This comes with several benefits:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://medium.com/mindorks/implementation-vs-api-in-gradle-3-0-494c817a6fa\">https://medium.com/mindorks/implementation-vs-api-in-gradle-3-0-494c817a6fa</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Calling startActivity() from outside of an Activity exception</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">    android.util.AndroidRuntimeException:</span> Calling startActivity() from outside of\n        an Activity  <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span> requires the FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK flag. Is this\n        really what you want?\n    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">at</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">android.app.ContextImpl.startActivity(ContextImpl.java:912)\n</span>\n    Solution :\n    Intent intent = new Intent(<span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>, YourActivity.class)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span>\n    intent.<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK);\n</span>    <span class=\"hljs-built_in\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">context</span>.startActivity(intent)<span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">;</span></pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Keep these things in mind for making library','','inherit','closed','closed','','421-revision-v1','','','2019-07-22 10:49:46','2019-07-22 09:49:46','',421,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/22/421-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(431,1,'2019-07-23 06:47:54','2019-07-23 05:47:54','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><em>Don\'t do this</em>. This would appear in the version control system.</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong> </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use <code>applicationIdSuffix</code> for <em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a> to be able to install both <em>debug</em> and <em>release</em> apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Proguard configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 06:47:54','2019-07-23 05:47:54','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(433,1,'2019-07-23 06:56:00','2019-07-23 05:56:00','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong> We recommend to have a look at the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a> before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong> In your app\'s <code>build.gradle</code> you will need to define the <code>signingConfigs</code> for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong> </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use <code>applicationIdSuffix</code> for <em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a> to be able to install both <em>debug</em> and <em>release</em> apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Proguard configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 06:56:00','2019-07-23 05:56:00','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(434,1,'2019-07-23 06:56:57','2019-07-23 05:56:57','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong> We recommend to have a look at the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a> before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong> In your app\'s <code>build.gradle</code> you will need to define the <code>signingConfigs</code> for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong> </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use <code>applicationIdSuffix</code> for <em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a> to be able to install both <em>debug</em> and <em>release</em> apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Proguard configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 06:56:57','2019-07-23 05:56:57','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(435,1,'2019-07-23 06:57:20','2019-07-23 05:57:20','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong> We recommend to have a look at the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a> before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong> In your app\'s <code>build.gradle</code> you will need to define the <code>signingConfigs</code> for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong> </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use <code>applicationIdSuffix</code> for <em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a> to be able to install both <em>debug</em> and <em>release</em> apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Proguard configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 06:57:20','2019-07-23 05:57:20','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(436,1,'2019-07-23 06:57:42','2019-07-23 05:57:42','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong> We recommend to have a look at the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a> before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong> In your app\'s <code>build.gradle</code> you will need to define the <code>signingConfigs</code> for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong> </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use <code>applicationIdSuffix</code> for <em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a> to be able to install both <em>debug</em> and <em>release</em> apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Proguard configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 06:57:42','2019-07-23 05:57:42','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(437,1,'2019-07-23 06:58:35','2019-07-23 05:58:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong> We recommend to have a look at the <a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a> before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong> In your app\'s <code>build.gradle</code> you will need to define the <code>signingConfigs</code> for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong> </h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use <code>applicationIdSuffix</code> for <em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a> to be able to install both <em>debug</em> and <em>release</em> apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Proguard</strong> <strong>configuration</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 06:58:35','2019-07-23 05:58:35','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(439,1,'2019-07-23 07:06:35','2019-07-23 06:06:35','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"build-process\">The build process</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process involves many tools and processes that convert your project into an Android Application Package (APK). The build process is very flexible, so it\'s useful to understand some of what is happening under the hood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://developer.android.com/images/tools/studio/build-process_2x.png\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>&nbsp;The build process of a typical Android app module.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process for a typical Android app module, as shown in figure 1, follows these general steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>The compilers convert your source code into DEX (Dalvik Executable) files, which include the bytecode that runs on Android devices, and everything else into compiled resources.</li><li>The APK Packager combines the DEX files and compiled resources into a single APK. Before your app can be installed and deployed onto an Android device, however, the APK must be signed.</li><li>The APK Packager signs your APK using either the debug or release keystore:<ol type=\"a\"><li>If you are building a debug version of your app, that is, an app you intend only for testing and profiling, the packager signs your app with the debug keystore. Android Studio automatically configures new projects with a debug keystore.</li><li>If you are building a release version of your app that you intend to release externally, the packager signs your app with the release keystore. To create a release keystore, read about&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/publish/app-signing.html#studio\">signing your app in Android Studio</a>.</li></ol></li><li>Before generating your final APK, the packager uses the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/command-line/zipalign.html\">zipalign</a>&nbsp;tool to optimize your app to use less memory when running on a device.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of the build process, you have either a debug APK or release APK of your app that you can use to deploy, test, or release to external users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong>&nbsp;We recommend to have a look at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a>&nbsp;before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong>&nbsp;In your app\'s&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;you will need to define the&nbsp;<code>signingConfigs</code>&nbsp;for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong>&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use&nbsp;<code>applicationIdSuffix</code>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a>&nbsp;to be able to install both&nbsp;<em>debug</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>release</em>&nbsp;apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Proguard</strong> <strong>configuration</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Refrences:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 07:06:35','2019-07-23 06:06:35','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(441,1,'2019-07-23 07:11:17','2019-07-23 06:11:17','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"build-process\">The build process</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process involves many tools and processes that convert your project into an Android Application Package (APK). The build process is very flexible, so it\'s useful to understand some of what is happening under the hood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":475,\"height\":534} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"https://developer.android.com/images/tools/studio/build-process_2x.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"475\" height=\"534\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>&nbsp;The build process of a typical Android app module.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process for a typical Android app module, as shown in figure 1, follows these general steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>The compilers convert your source code into DEX (Dalvik Executable) files, which include the bytecode that runs on Android devices, and everything else into compiled resources.</li><li>The APK Packager combines the DEX files and compiled resources into a single APK. Before your app can be installed and deployed onto an Android device, however, the APK must be signed.</li><li>The APK Packager signs your APK using either the debug or release keystore:<ol type=\"a\"><li>If you are building a debug version of your app, that is, an app you intend only for testing and profiling, the packager signs your app with the debug keystore. Android Studio automatically configures new projects with a debug keystore.</li><li>If you are building a release version of your app that you intend to release externally, the packager signs your app with the release keystore. To create a release keystore, read about&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/publish/app-signing.html#studio\">signing your app in Android Studio</a>.</li></ol></li><li>Before generating your final APK, the packager uses the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/command-line/zipalign.html\">zipalign</a>&nbsp;tool to optimize your app to use less memory when running on a device.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of the build process, you have either a debug APK or release APK of your app that you can use to deploy, test, or release to external users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong>&nbsp;We recommend to have a look at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a>&nbsp;before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong>&nbsp;In your app\'s&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;you will need to define the&nbsp;<code>signingConfigs</code>&nbsp;for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong>&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use&nbsp;<code>applicationIdSuffix</code>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a>&nbsp;to be able to install both&nbsp;<em>debug</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>release</em>&nbsp;apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Proguard</strong> <strong>configuration</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 07:11:17','2019-07-23 06:11:17','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(442,1,'2019-07-23 12:12:24','2019-07-23 11:12:24','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"build-process\">The build process</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process involves many tools and processes that convert your project into an Android Application Package (APK). The build process is very flexible, so it\'s useful to understand some of what is happening under the hood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":475,\"height\":534} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"https://developer.android.com/images/tools/studio/build-process_2x.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"475\" height=\"534\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>&nbsp;The build process of a typical Android app module.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process for a typical Android app module, as shown in figure 1, follows these general steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>The compilers convert your source code into DEX (Dalvik Executable) files, which include the bytecode that runs on Android devices, and everything else into compiled resources.</li><li>The APK Packager combines the DEX files and compiled resources into a single APK. Before your app can be installed and deployed onto an Android device, however, the APK must be signed.</li><li>The APK Packager signs your APK using either the debug or release keystore:<ol type=\"a\"><li>If you are building a debug version of your app, that is, an app you intend only for testing and profiling, the packager signs your app with the debug keystore. Android Studio automatically configures new projects with a debug keystore.</li><li>If you are building a release version of your app that you intend to release externally, the packager signs your app with the release keystore. To create a release keystore, read about&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/publish/app-signing.html#studio\">signing your app in Android Studio</a>.</li></ol></li><li>Before generating your final APK, the packager uses the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/command-line/zipalign.html\">zipalign</a>&nbsp;tool to optimize your app to use less memory when running on a device.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of the build process, you have either a debug APK or release APK of your app that you can use to deploy, test, or release to external users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong>&nbsp;We recommend to have a look at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a>&nbsp;before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong>&nbsp;In your app\'s&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;you will need to define the&nbsp;<code>signingConfigs</code>&nbsp;for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong>&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use&nbsp;<code>applicationIdSuffix</code>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a>&nbsp;to be able to install both&nbsp;<em>debug</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>release</em>&nbsp;apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Proguard</strong> <strong>configuration</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reference:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build\">https://developer.android.com/studio/build</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 12:12:24','2019-07-23 11:12:24','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(444,1,'2019-07-23 12:15:08','2019-07-23 11:15:08','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"build-process\">The build process</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process involves many tools and processes that convert your project into an Android Application Package (APK). The build process is very flexible, so it\'s useful to understand some of what is happening under the hood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":475,\"height\":534} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"https://developer.android.com/images/tools/studio/build-process_2x.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"475\" height=\"534\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>&nbsp;The build process of a typical Android app module.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process for a typical Android app module, as shown in figure 1, follows these general steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>The compilers convert your source code into DEX (Dalvik Executable) files, which include the bytecode that runs on Android devices, and everything else into compiled resources.</li><li>The APK Packager combines the DEX files and compiled resources into a single APK. Before your app can be installed and deployed onto an Android device, however, the APK must be signed.</li><li>The APK Packager signs your APK using either the debug or release keystore:<ol type=\"a\"><li>If you are building a debug version of your app, that is, an app you intend only for testing and profiling, the packager signs your app with the debug keystore. Android Studio automatically configures new projects with a debug keystore.</li><li>If you are building a release version of your app that you intend to release externally, the packager signs your app with the release keystore. To create a release keystore, read about&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/publish/app-signing.html#studio\">signing your app in Android Studio</a>.</li></ol></li><li>Before generating your final APK, the packager uses the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/command-line/zipalign.html\">zipalign</a>&nbsp;tool to optimize your app to use less memory when running on a device.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of the build process, you have either a debug APK or release APK of your app that you can use to deploy, test, or release to external users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong>&nbsp;We recommend to have a look at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a>&nbsp;before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong>&nbsp;In your app\'s&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;you will need to define the&nbsp;<code>signingConfigs</code>&nbsp;for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong>&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use&nbsp;<code>applicationIdSuffix</code>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a>&nbsp;to be able to install both&nbsp;<em>debug</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>release</em>&nbsp;apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Proguard</strong> <strong>configuration</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider <a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 id=\"leakcanary\">LeakCanary</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>LeakCanary is a memory leak detection library for Android.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"width\":649,\"height\":315} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image is-resized\"><img src=\"https://github.com/square/leakcanary/wiki/assets/screenshot-2.0.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"649\" height=\"315\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>LeakCanary’s knowledge of the internals of the Android Framework gives it a unique ability to narrow down the cause of each leak, helping developers dramatically reduce OutOfMemoryError crashes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Add LeakCanary to <code>build.gradle</code>: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">dependencies {\n  // <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">debug</span>Implementation because LeakCanary should only run <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">in</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">debug</span> builds.\n  <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">debug</span>Implementation \'com.squareup.leakcanary:leakcanary-android:<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2.0</span>-alpha-<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>\'\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>That’s it, there is no code change needed!</strong>&nbsp;LeakCanary will automatically show a notification when a memory leak is detected in debug builds.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reference:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build\">https://developer.android.com/studio/build</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 12:15:08','2019-07-23 11:15:08','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(446,1,'2019-07-23 12:34:54','2019-07-23 11:34:54','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gradle is a build automation tool often used for JVM languages such as Java, Groovy or Scala. Gradle can be configured to run&nbsp;<code>Tasks</code>&nbsp;which do things like compile&nbsp;<code>jar</code>s, run tests, create documentation and much more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gardle is an advanced general purpose build management. It is an open source build automation system that builds up on ANT, Maven and lvy repositories. It supports groovy based Domain Specific Language (DSL) over the XML.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"build-process\">The build process</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process involves many tools and processes that convert your project into an Android Application Package (APK). The build process is very flexible, so it\'s useful to understand some of what is happening under the hood.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"width\":475,\"height\":534} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter is-resized\"><img src=\"https://developer.android.com/images/tools/studio/build-process_2x.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"475\" height=\"534\"/></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>&nbsp;The build process of a typical Android app module.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The build process for a typical Android app module, as shown in figure 1, follows these general steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>The compilers convert your source code into DEX (Dalvik Executable) files, which include the bytecode that runs on Android devices, and everything else into compiled resources.</li><li>The APK Packager combines the DEX files and compiled resources into a single APK. Before your app can be installed and deployed onto an Android device, however, the APK must be signed.</li><li>The APK Packager signs your APK using either the debug or release keystore:<ol type=\"a\"><li>If you are building a debug version of your app, that is, an app you intend only for testing and profiling, the packager signs your app with the debug keystore. Android Studio automatically configures new projects with a debug keystore.</li><li>If you are building a release version of your app that you intend to release externally, the packager signs your app with the release keystore. To create a release keystore, read about&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/publish/app-signing.html#studio\">signing your app in Android Studio</a>.</li></ol></li><li>Before generating your final APK, the packager uses the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/command-line/zipalign.html\">zipalign</a>&nbsp;tool to optimize your app to use less memory when running on a device.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At the end of the build process, you have either a debug APK or release APK of your app that you can use to deploy, test, or release to external users.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>Gradle configuration</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>General structure.</strong>&nbsp;Follow&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build/index.html\">Google\'s guide on Gradle for Android</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>minSdkVersion: 21</strong>&nbsp;We recommend to have a look at the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#Platform\">Android version usage chart</a>&nbsp;before defining the minimum API required. Remember that the statistics given are global statistics and may differ when targeting a specific regional/demographic market. It is worth mentioning that some material design features are only available on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and above. And also, from API 21, the multidex support library is not needed anymore.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> <br><strong>Passwords.</strong>&nbsp;In your app\'s&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;you will need to define the&nbsp;<code>signingConfigs</code>&nbsp;for the release build. Here is what you should avoid: <br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em><strong>Don\'t do this</strong></em><strong>. </strong>This would appear in the version control system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-class\">signingConfigs </span>{\n    <span class=\"hljs-class\">release </span>{\n        <span class=\"hljs-comment\" style=\"color: rgb(118, 110, 107);\">// DON\'T DO THIS!!</span>\n        storeFile file(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n        storePassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password123\"</span>\n        keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n        keyPassword <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"password789\"</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Instead, make a&nbsp;<code>gradle.properties</code>&nbsp;file which should&nbsp;<em>not</em>&nbsp;be added to the version control system:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>KEYSTORE_PASSWORD=password123\nKEY_PASSWORD=password789\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That file is automatically imported by Gradle, so you can use it in&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code>&nbsp;as such:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">signingConfigs {\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">try</span> {\n            storeFile <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">file</span>(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"myapp.keystore\"</span>)\n            storePassword KEYSTORE_PASSWORD\n            keyAlias <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"thekey\"</span>\n            keyPassword KEY_PASSWORD\n        }\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">catch</span> (<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">ex</span>) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">throw</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">new</span> InvalidUserDataException(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"You should define KEYSTORE_PASSWORD and KEY_PASSWORD in gradle.properties.\"</span>)\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>Use different package name for non-release builds</strong>&nbsp;</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Use&nbsp;<code>applicationIdSuffix</code>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<em>debug</em><a href=\"http://tools.android.com/tech-docs/new-build-system/user-guide#TOC-Build-Types\">build type</a>&nbsp;to be able to install both&nbsp;<em>debug</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>release</em>&nbsp;apk on the same device (do this also for custom build types, if you need any). This will be especially valuable after your app has been published. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    buildTypes {\n        debug {\n            applicationIdSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'.debug\'</span>\n            versionNameSuffix <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'-DEBUG\'</span>\n        }\n\n        release {\n            // ...\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4><strong>How to recompile with -Xlint:deprecation</strong></h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> adding this to&nbsp;<code>build.gradle</code></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">allprojects {\n    ...\n\n    gradle<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.projectsEvaluated</span> {\n        tasks.withType(JavaCompile) {\n            options<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.compilerArgs</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"-Xlint:deprecation\"</span>\n        }\n    }   \n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"building_gradle_minify\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#building_gradle_minify\">Removing unused resources and Java classes via resource shrinking</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Gradle build system for Android supports resource shrinking at build time. This automatically removes resources that are unused from the packaged application. In addition to that, this also removes unnecessary resources from libraries you are depending on. This can hugely reduce the size of your application.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To enable resource shrinking, update your build file similar to the following snippet.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">android {\n    ...\n\n    buildTypes {\n        release {\n            minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            shrinkResources <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n            proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-android.txt\'), <span class=\"hljs-symbol\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard</span>-rules.pro\'\n        }\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3 id=\"defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\"><a href=\"http://www.vogella.com/tutorials/AndroidBuild/article.html#defining-dependencies-and-keeping-the-version-external\">Defining dependencies and keeping the version external</a></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"bb4a\">1. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Module level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">25</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n    playServiceVersion = \'<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">10</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2</span>.<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">0</span>\'\n}\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    \n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$playServiceVersion\"</span>\n   ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4 id=\"mce_12\">2. Manage dependencies versions in same gradle file Project level</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>build.gradle(Project level)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">buildscript {\n    ...\n}\n\nallprojects {\n    ...\n}\n...\n\next {\n    supportLibraryVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'23.4.0\'</span>\n    playServicesVersion = <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'9.2.1\'</span>\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> build.gradle(Module level) </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">apply plugin: \'com.android.application\'\nandroid {\n      ...\n    defaultConfig <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    buildTypes <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n    productFlavors <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">{...}</span>\n}\n...\n\ndependencies {\n    // <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Android</span> supported libraries\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:appcompat-v7:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.android.support:design:$rootProject.supportLibraryVersion\"</span> \n\n    //<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Google</span> play services\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>\n    compile <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"com.google.android.gms:play-services-fitness:$rootProject.playServiceVersion\"</span>  \n    ...\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3><strong>Proguard</strong> <strong>configuration</strong></h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"http://proguard.sourceforge.net/\">ProGuard</a>&nbsp;is normally used on Android projects to shrink and obfuscate the packaged code.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether you are using ProGuard or not depends on your project configuration. Usually you would configure Gradle to use ProGuard when building a release APK.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\"><span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">buildTypes</span> {\n    <span class=\"hljs-section\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">debug</span> {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">minifyEnabled</span> <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">false</span>\n    }\n    release {\n        <span class=\"hljs-attribute\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">signingConfig</span> signingConfigs.release\n        minifyEnabled <span class=\"hljs-literal\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">true</span>\n        proguardFiles getDefaultProguardFile(<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-android.txt\'</span>), <span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\'proguard-rules.pro\'</span>\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to determine which code has to be preserved and which code can be discarded or obfuscated, you have to specify one or more entry points to your code. These entry points are typically classes with main methods, applets, midlets, activities, etc. Android framework uses a default configuration which can be found from&nbsp;<code>SDK_HOME/tools/proguard/proguard-android.txt</code>. Using the above configuration, custom project-specific ProGuard rules, as defined in&nbsp;<code>my-project/app/proguard-rules.pro</code>, will be appended to the default configuration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common problem related to ProGuard is to see the application crashing on startup with&nbsp;<code>ClassNotFoundException</code>&nbsp;or&nbsp;<code>NoSuchFieldException</code>&nbsp;or similar, even though the build command (i.e.&nbsp;<code>assembleRelease</code>) succeeded without warnings. This means one out of two things:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list {\"ordered\":true} -->\n<ol><li>ProGuard has removed the class, enum, method, field or annotation, considering it\'s not required.</li><li>ProGuard has obfuscated (renamed) the class, enum or field name, but it\'s being used indirectly by its original name, i.e. through Java reflection.</li></ol>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/usage.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been removed. Check&nbsp;<code>app/build/outputs/proguard/release/mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;to see if the object in question has been obfuscated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In order to prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>stripping away</em>&nbsp;needed classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keep</code>&nbsp;options to your ProGuard config:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keep class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To prevent ProGuard from&nbsp;<em>obfuscating</em>&nbsp;classes or class members, add a&nbsp;<code>keepnames</code>:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>-keepnames class com.futurice.project.MyClass { *; }\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Read more at&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.guardsquare.com/en/proguard/manual/examples\">Proguard</a>&nbsp;for examples.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Early in your project, make and test release build</strong>&nbsp;to check whether ProGuard rules are correctly retaining your dependencies. Also whenever you include new libraries or update their dependencies, make a release build and test the APK on a device. Don\'t wait until your app is finally version \"1.0\" to make a release build, you might get several unpleasant surprises and a short time to fix them.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Tip.</strong>&nbsp;Save the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for every release that you publish to your users. By retaining a copy of the&nbsp;<code>mapping.txt</code>&nbsp;file for each release build, you ensure that you can debug a problem if a user encounters a bug and submits an obfuscated stack trace.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>DexGuard</strong>. If you need hard-core tools for optimizing, and specially obfuscating release code, consider <a href=\"http://www.saikoa.com/dexguard\">DexGuard</a>, a commercial software made by the same team that built ProGuard. It can also easily split Dex files to solve the 65k methods limitation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 id=\"leakcanary\">LeakCanary</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>LeakCanary is a memory leak detection library for Android.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"width\":649,\"height\":315} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image is-resized\"><img src=\"https://github.com/square/leakcanary/wiki/assets/screenshot-2.0.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"649\" height=\"315\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>LeakCanary’s knowledge of the internals of the Android Framework gives it a unique ability to narrow down the cause of each leak, helping developers dramatically reduce OutOfMemoryError crashes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Add LeakCanary to <code>build.gradle</code>: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">dependencies {\n  // <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">debug</span>Implementation because LeakCanary should only run <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">in</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">debug</span> builds.\n  <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">debug</span>Implementation \'com.squareup.leakcanary:leakcanary-android:<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">2.0</span>-alpha-<span class=\"hljs-number\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">3</span>\'\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>That’s it, there is no code change needed!</strong>&nbsp;LeakCanary will automatically show a notification when a memory leak is detected in debug builds.\n\n</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://square.github.io/leakcanary/getting_started/\">https://square.github.io/leakcanary/getting_started/</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:separator -->\n<hr class=\"wp-block-separator\"/>\n<!-- /wp:separator -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Reference:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><a href=\"https://developer.android.com/studio/build\">https://developer.android.com/studio/build</a></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->','Android Gradle','','inherit','closed','closed','','269-revision-v1','','','2019-07-23 12:34:54','2019-07-23 11:34:54','',269,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/07/23/269-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(448,1,'2019-08-22 12:28:05','2019-08-22 11:28:05','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Toolbar back arrow icon not align with Title</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":452} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/asdasd.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-452\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The navigation button is vertically aligned within the Toolbar\'s minimum height, if set. So if you set&nbsp;<em>minHeight</em>&nbsp;attribute the same as your toolbar height (<em>layout_height</em>&nbsp;), the back arrow will be centered vertically. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    &lt;com<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.google</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.material</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appbar</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.AppBarLayout</span>\n        android:layout_width=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        android:layout_height=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span> \n        android:theme=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@style/AppTheme.AppBarOverlay\"</span>\n        app:elevation=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"0dp\"</span>&gt;\n\n        &lt;androidx<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appcompat</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.widget</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.Toolbar</span>\n            android:id=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/toolbar\"</span>\n            android:layout_width=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n            android:layout_height=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"70dp\"</span>\n            android:minHeight=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"70dp\"</span> \n            app:contentInsetStart=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"0dp\"</span> &gt;\n            \n            ....\n            ....\n        &lt;/androidx<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appcompat</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.widget</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.Toolbar</span>&gt;\n    &lt;/com<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.google</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.material</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appbar</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.AppBarLayout</span>&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>For remove left margin from actionbar custom layout , you can simply add XML attributes to remove content insets. </li><li> Simply use&nbsp;<code>app:elevation=\"0dp\"</code>&nbsp;inside \"AppBarLayout\" to remove the shadow. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','AntionBar or Toolbar','','publish','open','open','','antionbar-or-toolbar','','','2019-08-22 12:31:20','2019-08-22 11:31:20','',0,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/?p=448',0,'post','',0),(449,1,'2019-08-22 12:18:54','2019-08-22 11:18:54','','R0zwa','','inherit','open','closed','','r0zwa','','','2019-08-22 12:18:54','2019-08-22 11:18:54','',448,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/R0zwa.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(450,1,'2019-08-22 12:28:05','2019-08-22 11:28:05','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Back arrow button not placed in center in toolbar in android</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":449} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/R0zwa.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-449\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The navigation button is vertically aligned within the Toolbar\'s minimum height, if set. So if you set <em>minHeight</em> attribute the same as your toolbar height (<em>layout_height</em> ), the back arrow will be centered vertically. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    &lt;com<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.google</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.material</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appbar</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.AppBarLayout</span>\n        android:layout_width=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        android:layout_height=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span> \n        android:theme=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@style/AppTheme.AppBarOverlay\"</span>\n        app:elevation=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"0dp\"</span>&gt;\n\n        &lt;androidx<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appcompat</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.widget</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.Toolbar</span>\n            android:id=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/toolbar\"</span>\n            android:layout_width=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n            android:layout_height=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"70dp\"</span>\n            android:minHeight=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"70dp\"</span> \n            app:contentInsetStart=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"0dp\"</span> &gt;\n            \n            ....\n            ....\n        &lt;/androidx<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appcompat</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.widget</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.Toolbar</span>&gt;\n    &lt;/com<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.google</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.material</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appbar</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.AppBarLayout</span>&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>For remove left margin from actionbar custom layout , you can simply add XML attributes to remove content insets. </li><li> Simply use <code>app:elevation=\"0dp\"</code> inside \"AppBarLayout\" to remove the shadow. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','AntionBar or Toolbar','','inherit','closed','closed','','448-revision-v1','','','2019-08-22 12:28:05','2019-08-22 11:28:05','',448,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/08/22/448-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(452,1,'2019-08-22 12:31:12','2019-08-22 11:31:12','','asdasd','','inherit','open','closed','','asdasd','','','2019-08-22 12:31:12','2019-08-22 11:31:12','',448,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/asdasd.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(453,1,'2019-08-22 12:31:18','2019-08-22 11:31:18','<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":4} -->\n<h4>Toolbar back arrow icon not align with Title</h4>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":452} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"http://blogs.appsfeature.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/asdasd.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-452\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The navigation button is vertically aligned within the Toolbar\'s minimum height, if set. So if you set&nbsp;<em>minHeight</em>&nbsp;attribute the same as your toolbar height (<em>layout_height</em>&nbsp;), the back arrow will be centered vertically. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    &lt;com<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.google</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.material</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appbar</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.AppBarLayout</span>\n        android:layout_width=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n        android:layout_height=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"wrap_content\"</span> \n        android:theme=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@style/AppTheme.AppBarOverlay\"</span>\n        app:elevation=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"0dp\"</span>&gt;\n\n        &lt;androidx<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appcompat</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.widget</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.Toolbar</span>\n            android:id=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"@+id/toolbar\"</span>\n            android:layout_width=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"match_parent\"</span>\n            android:layout_height=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"70dp\"</span>\n            android:minHeight=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"70dp\"</span> \n            app:contentInsetStart=<span class=\"hljs-string\" style=\"color: rgb(123, 151, 38);\">\"0dp\"</span> &gt;\n            \n            ....\n            ....\n        &lt;/androidx<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appcompat</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.widget</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.Toolbar</span>&gt;\n    &lt;/com<span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.google</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.android</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.material</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.appbar</span><span class=\"hljs-selector-class\" style=\"color: rgb(242, 44, 64);\">.AppBarLayout</span>&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>For remove left margin from actionbar custom layout , you can simply add XML attributes to remove content insets. </li><li> Simply use&nbsp;<code>app:elevation=\"0dp\"</code>&nbsp;inside \"AppBarLayout\" to remove the shadow. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->','AntionBar or Toolbar','','inherit','closed','closed','','448-revision-v1','','','2019-08-22 12:31:18','2019-08-22 11:31:18','',448,'http://blogs.appsfeature.com/index.php/2019/08/22/448-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (455,1,'2019-09-18 08:38:54','2019-09-18 07:38:54','<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> The DayNight functionality in AppCompat allows your app to easily switch between a dark ⚫ and light ⚪ theme. This has many benefits for your users, from saving power on OLED displays, to increasing usability for people with reduced-vision, and more. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"97e1\">setDefaultNightMode</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first API we provide to do that is&nbsp;<code>AppCompatDelegate.<a href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/appcompat/app/AppCompatDelegate#setDefaultNightMode(int)\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">setDefaultNightMode()</a></code>, which takes one of the follow values:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><code><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/appcompat/app/AppCompatDelegate.html#MODE_NIGHT_NO\" target=\"_blank\">MODE_NIGHT_NO</a></code>. Always use the day (light) theme.</li><li><code><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/appcompat/app/AppCompatDelegate.html#MODE_NIGHT_YES\" target=\"_blank\">MODE_NIGHT_YES</a></code>. Always use the night (dark) theme.</li><li><code><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/appcompat/app/AppCompatDelegate.html#MODE_NIGHT_FOLLOW_SYSTEM\" target=\"_blank\">MODE_NIGHT_FOLLOW_SYSTEM</a></code>&nbsp;<em>(default)</em>. This setting follows the system’s setting, which on Android Q and above is a system setting (more on this below).</li><li><code>MODE_NIGHT_AUTO_BATTERY</code>. Changes to dark when the device has its ‘Battery Saver’ feature enabled, light otherwise.<br>✨<strong><em>New in v1.1.0-alpha03.</em></strong></li><li><code>MODE_NIGHT_AUTO_TIME</code>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<code><a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developer.android.com/reference/androidx/appcompat/app/AppCompatDelegate.html#MODE_NIGHT_AUTO\" target=\"_blank\">MODE_NIGHT_AUTO</a></code>. Changes between day/night based on the time of day.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> The method is static so you can call it at any time. The value you set is&nbsp;<strong>not</strong>&nbsp;persisted across process starts though, therefore you need to set it every time your app process is started. I recommend setting it in your application class (if you have one) like so: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    public <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyApplication</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Application</span> </span>{\n\n        public void onCreate() {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">super</span>.onCreate();\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppPreferences</span>.isDayMode(<span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">this</span>)) {\n                <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_NO</span>);\n            } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">else</span> {\n                <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_YES</span>);\n            }\n        }\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p> Previously you could do the following quite happily, without AppCompat needing to recreate the Activity: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">public <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyActivity</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Activity</span> </span>{\n    \n    public void onCreate(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Bundle</span> icicle) {\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">super</span>.onCreate(icicle);\n        getDelegate().setLocalNightMode(\n                <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_YES</span>);\n    }\n}</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1 id=\"4e1e\">In-app setting</h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is recommended to provide a way for the user to override the default theme in your app. The recommended options and strings are:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>‘Light’ (<code>MODE_NIGHT_NO</code>)</li><li>‘Dark’ (<code>MODE_NIGHT_YES</code>)</li><li>‘Set by Battery Saver’ (<code>MODE_NIGHT_AUTO_BATTERY</code>).<em><br>Only show on Android Pie and below. This should be your app’s default when shown.</em></li><li>‘Use system default’ (<code>MODE_NIGHT_FOLLOW_SYSTEM</code>).<br><em>Only show on Android Q and above. This should be your app’s default when shown.</em></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A common way to do to implement would be via a&nbsp;<a rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" href=\"https://developer.android.com/guide/topics/ui/settings/components-and-attributes\" target=\"_blank\">ListPreference</a>, calling to&nbsp;<code>setDefaultNightMode()</code>&nbsp;when the value changes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2 id=\"6eb8\">Using your own resources for dark/light</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>AppCompat in simple terms is just enabling the use of the&nbsp;<code>night</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>notnight</code>&nbsp;resource qualifiers. These have actually been available in the platform since API 8, but were previously only used in very specific scenarios.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Under the hood&nbsp;<code>Theme.AppCompat.DayNight</code>&nbsp;is implemented as so:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>res/values/themes.xml</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;style name=\"Theme.AppCompat.DayNight\" <br>       parent=\"Theme.AppCompat.Light\" /&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>res/values-night/themes.xml</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:preformatted -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">&lt;style name=\"Theme.AppCompat.DayNight\" <br>       parent=\"Theme.AppCompat\" /&gt;</pre>\n<!-- /wp:preformatted -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This means that you can also provide alternative resources for your light and dark UIs. Just use the&nbsp;<code>-<strong>night</strong></code>&nbsp;qualifier on your resource folders:&nbsp;<code>drawable-night</code>,&nbsp;<code>values-night</code>, etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Example:</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In your Application class</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    public <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyApplication</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Application</span> </span>{\n\n        <span class=\"hljs-meta\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">@Override</span>\n        <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">protected</span> void attachBaseContext(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Context</span> base) {\n            initTheme(base);\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">super</span>.attachBaseContext(base);  \n        }\n\n        public void initTheme(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Context</span> context) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (!<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppPreferences</span>.isDayMode(context)) {\n                <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_YES</span>);\n            } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">else</span> {\n                <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_NO</span>);\n            }\n        } \n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In your Activity class</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); color: rgb(104, 97, 94); padding: 0.5em;\">    public <span class=\"hljs-class\"><span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">class</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">MyActivity</span> <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">extends</span> <span class=\"hljs-title\" style=\"color: rgb(64, 126, 231);\">Activity</span> </span>{\n\n        public void onCreate(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Bundle</span> icicle) {\n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">super</span>.onCreate(icicle);\n            setDayNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppPreferences</span>.isDayMode(activity));\n        }\n\n        public void setDayNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">Context</span> context, boolean isDayMode) { \n            <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (context instanceof <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatActivity</span>) {\n                ((<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatActivity</span>) context).getDelegate().setLocalNightMode( isDayMode\n                        ? <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_NO</span> : <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_YES</span> );\n                <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (isDayMode) {\n                    <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_NO</span>);\n                } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">else</span> {\n                    <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_YES</span>);\n                }\n            } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">else</span> {\n                <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">if</span> (isDayMode) {\n                    <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_NO</span>);\n                } <span class=\"hljs-keyword\" style=\"color: rgb(102, 102, 234);\">else</span> {\n                    <span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.setDefaultNightMode(<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">AppCompatDelegate</span>.<span class=\"hljs-type\" style=\"color: rgb(223, 83, 32);\">MODE_NIGHT_YES</span>);\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }</pre>\n<!-- /wp:html -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>res/values/colors.xml</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:html -->\n<pre class=\"hljs\" style=\"display: block; overflow-x: auto; background: rgb(241, 239, 238); c